{"term":"1956","caseName":"Mallory v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/521","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 01, 1957 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13203","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 521, Andrew R.Mallory versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":15.463,"duration":15.46},{"text":"Mr. Bryant.","start":15.463,"stop":19.667,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, Associate Justices, may it please the Court.","start":19.667,"stop":27.613,"duration":7.95},{"text":"The case for the Court, Andrew Mallory versus United States, we believe presents three important questions.","start":27.613,"stop":39.661,"duration":12.05},{"text":"The first, whether or not the lower courts in the District of Columbia Circuit properly adhered to the pronouncements of this Court in McNabb versus United States and reiterated in Upshaw versus United States relative to alleged confessions of the petition.","start":39.661,"stop":61.122,"duration":21.46},{"text":"Number two, I believe that the important question is whether or not the consent allegedly given to the police by the petitioner herein for the search of his home for certain items of clothing while he was arrested and then the police headquarters measured up to that standard of voluntariness which the federal jurisdiction has adopted for itself.","start":61.122,"stop":88.596,"duration":27.47},{"text":"And thirdly, whether or not the trial court's comment in answer to a question by the jury after deliberating some four or four and a half hours about the fate of the petitioner in the event that the jury did not impose a death penalty, was proper under the circumstances.","start":88.596,"stop":111.736,"duration":23.14},{"text":"Now, the factual picture which -- out of which these questions arises is briefly as follows.","start":111.736,"stop":119.884,"duration":8.15},{"text":"On April 7th, 1954, a woman was allegedly raped in the 1200 Block of 12th Street Northwest in the District of Columbia in the basement of an apartment house in which she lived.","start":119.884,"stop":135.75,"duration":15.87},{"text":"The next day, at about 2:30, the petitioner was arrested in the Northeast section of Washington D.C. and taken to police headquarters at 13 Indiana Avenue, Northwest.","start":135.75,"stop":149.977,"duration":14.23},{"text":"Immediately upon his arrival at the police headquarters, he was interrogated in the so-called identification room at the police headquarters.","start":149.977,"stop":159.005,"duration":9.03},{"text":"The arrival was pitched at about 3 o'clock in the afternoon.","start":159.005,"stop":165.44,"duration":6.44},{"text":"Here, the petitioner was questioned by at least seven or eight officers of the Sex Squad between 3 o'clock and shortly after 4:00 that he -- and then some times between 4:00 and 5:00 during that questioning, the petitioner denied any implication in the crime.","start":165.44,"stop":186.135,"duration":20.69},{"text":"Some times between 4 and 5 o'clock, the police inquired of the petitioner and his two nephews, the children of his half brother who was a janitor of the apartment which the alleged crime occurred and who also in custody.","start":186.135,"stop":201.899,"duration":15.76},{"text":"The police inquired as to whether or not they would take the lie detector test.","start":201.899,"stop":211.127,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Petitioner is alleged to have agreed to take a lie detector test along with the other two suspects.","start":211.127,"stop":217.659,"duration":6.53},{"text":"The man who was an expert at giving the examination was not immediately available and there was a waiting period of -- from about some time between 4 and 5 to about 7 o'clock.","start":217.659,"stop":232.51,"duration":14.85},{"text":"The officer eventually arrived, and after exposing the other two men who were in custody to the lie detector apparatus and the testing that goes on with it, the petitioner was called into the room some 120 feet away from the room in which he had been all the time.","start":232.51,"stop":253.394,"duration":20.88},{"text":"And there, in the lie detector room, which is a small room about the size enough to accommodate the machinery and the examiner and the -- and the subject, he was given the so-called “lie detector test.”","start":253.394,"stop":269.261,"duration":15.87},{"text":"His questioning immediately before -- questioning during the -- during the examination at which time he was attached to the machinery by various wires and hoses and other attachments.","start":269.261,"stop":281.961,"duration":12.7},{"text":"After the examination on the machine, he was subjected to still more questioning and some time between 9:30 and 9:45 p.m., according to the examining officer, he made certain oral admissions which implicated him in the crime.","start":281.961,"stop":298.516,"duration":16.56},{"text":"Thereupon, the examining officer called the two officers of the Sex Squad who were in charge of the case so to speak and indicated to those officers that the petitioner wanted to make a statement to them.","start":298.516,"stop":310.495,"duration":11.98},{"text":"At that time, the oral admission originally made to the examiner, speaking of the lie detector machine technician, were allegedly repeated to officers (Inaudible) I believe.","start":310.495,"stop":324.052,"duration":13.56},{"text":"After the admissions were made, one officer to another said, “Try to get a hold of the Commissioner\" having reference to the United States Commissioner and then for the District of Columbia.","start":324.052,"stop":338.392,"duration":14.34},{"text":"A call was put through to the commissioner at his home and he was at that time unavailable, that was sometimes after 10 o'clock p.m., the first mention of the commission.","start":338.392,"stop":349.882,"duration":11.49},{"text":"Thereupon, the petitioner set out under police supervision a written statement embodying what's he had said to the officers are.","start":349.882,"stop":363.083,"duration":13.2},{"text":"And immediately following the written statement, there was also a written consent to the officers to go to the premises and search certain areas and take from that area items or clothing.","start":363.083,"stop":381.174,"duration":18.09},{"text":"The confessions are -- unwritten were introduced an evidence over objection.","start":381.174,"stop":386.269,"duration":5.1},{"text":"The items of clothing which had been procured as the result of the so-called “consent to search” and which had been subjected to certain analysis by the Federal Bureau of Investigation and which should be -- reveal certain culminating characteristics were introduced to the evidence.","start":386.269,"stop":403.629,"duration":17.36},{"text":"The jury was instructed, when he took the case, in the usual fashion except that when it got down to the point of the verdicts by virtue of the peculiar characteristic of the District of Columbia statute which allows the jury to add to the verdict of guilty if they so find the defendant who's charged with rape, guilty.","start":403.629,"stop":426.015,"duration":22.39},{"text":"He might add the words with the death penalty.","start":426.015,"stop":429.168,"duration":3.15},{"text":"Because of that, Judge Holtzoff read to them the following, and I -- I think that in these circumstances, I should read the charge because it is critical.","start":429.168,"stop":444.042,"duration":14.87},{"text":"Beginning on page 5 -- page 105 of the record, if the Court please, the fourth paragraph beginning with “If you find the defendant guilty, you still have one more punishment”, the punishment provided by law for the crime of rape is either a death penalty or imprisonment for a term of years.","start":444.042,"stop":466.969,"duration":22.93},{"text":"The decision, whether the death penalty should be inflicted, is made by the jury.","start":466.969,"stop":471.595,"duration":4.63},{"text":"The jury has the right in the function of determining whether or not the death penalty should be inflicted on a rape case.","start":471.595,"stop":477.863,"duration":6.27},{"text":"Consequently, if you find the defendant guilty as charged, you must then decide also whether the death penalty should be imposed.","start":477.863,"stop":485.783,"duration":7.92},{"text":"If you unanimously reached the conclusion that the death penalty should be inflicted, then you may add to your verdict of guilty the words “with the death penalty”.","start":485.783,"stop":495.655,"duration":9.87},{"text":"In such case, and such as your verdict, it will then be mandatory on the Court to impose the death penalty.","start":495.655,"stop":501.74,"duration":6.09},{"text":"The Court will have no discretion under that.","start":501.74,"stop":504.369,"duration":2.63},{"text":"On the other hand, if you find the defendant guilty but you do not unanimously reach the conclusion that the death penalty should be inflicted, then your verdict should be simply guilty as charged without any addition to it.","start":504.369,"stop":516.388,"duration":12.02},{"text":"In that event, the defendant will be subject to imprisonment which the Court will impose but will not be subject to the death penalty.","start":516.388,"stop":523.59,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Whether the death penalty, should or should not be imposed, in case you find the defendant guilty is entirely within your discretion and you have a right to consider any circumstances or weigh in his considerations in reaching the conclusion on that point.","start":523.59,"stop":536.656,"duration":13.07},{"text":"That is the critical part of the Court's charge in the light of the question we raised here.","start":536.656,"stop":544.387,"duration":7.73},{"text":"If the Court please, after deliberating for something over four hours, we've indicated, the jury indicated that it wanted some explanation or some instructions from the Court and sent the Court a note which asks several questions.","start":544.387,"stop":567.019,"duration":22.63},{"text":"The Court deals with this note on page 106 of the record, the Court called counsel to the bench and showed there's a note indicating that the jury had asked one, “Have we other choice of verdicts than this four?”","start":567.019,"stop":582.868,"duration":15.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before -- may I?","start":582.868,"stop":584.018,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":584.018,"stop":584.214,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me for interrupting you --","start":584.214,"stop":585.588,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":585.588,"stop":585.914,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but if we had no more than that what you read on page 105 Mr. Bryant, have you or have you not a quarrel with that -- that portion of the initial charge made by the Court?","start":585.914,"stop":599.868,"duration":13.95}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I have no quarrel with the general brief.","start":599.868,"stop":601.074,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, that's -- that's not all right, difficulty arises on the response to the subsequent questions.","start":601.074,"stop":607.685,"duration":6.61}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":607.685,"stop":611.457,"duration":3.77},{"text":"The subsequent questions, I believe, were outlined on page 106 of the record, have we other choice of verdicts than these four.","start":611.457,"stop":619.715,"duration":8.26},{"text":"One, guilty with death penalty.","start":619.715,"stop":621.92,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Two, guilty as charged.","start":621.92,"stop":623.842,"duration":1.92},{"text":"Three, not guilty by reason of insanity.","start":623.842,"stop":626.62,"duration":2.78},{"text":"Four, not guilty.","start":626.62,"stop":628.546,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Now, the Court answered that question.","start":628.546,"stop":633.38,"duration":4.83},{"text":"Now, those four are the only possible verdicts, no other verdict is possible.","start":633.38,"stop":637.728,"duration":4.35},{"text":"Then the Court dealt with question number two.","start":637.728,"stop":640.557,"duration":2.83},{"text":"Question number two was, on number two above having reference to guilty as charged, \"Can we the jury be assured that the defendant legally be imprisoned for the remainder of his natural life?","start":640.557,"stop":652.782,"duration":12.23},{"text":"No possibility of release - in his sentence.\"","start":652.782,"stop":657.786,"duration":5},{"text":"The Court in response to that question said, \"I can give you no such assurance.","start":657.786,"stop":663.167,"duration":5.38},{"text":"I think I might explain to you that the maximum term the Court may impose is 30 years, but even if the Court imposes the maximum, and of course I can, even if the Court imposes the maximum, the Court also has to impose a minimum sentence.","start":663.167,"stop":677.655,"duration":14.49},{"text":"So that the longest term that the Court can impose would be an indeterminate sentence of 10 to 30 years.","start":677.655,"stop":683.087,"duration":5.43},{"text":"The minimum has to be not more than a third of the maximum.","start":683.087,"stop":686.638,"duration":3.55},{"text":"Then at the end of the minimum sentence, the Parole Board would have to decide whether the maximum should be served, or anything less than the maximum.","start":686.638,"stop":694.327,"duration":7.69},{"text":"So that I can give you no assurance that the defendant would legally be imprisoned for the remainder of his natural life if he's found guilty as charged.","start":694.327,"stop":702.035,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you Mr. Bryant?","start":702.035,"stop":703.674,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":703.674,"stop":704.448,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As a statement of what the law is in that regard, do you need to quarrel with it?","start":704.448,"stop":711.171,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, as a statement of what the law is, if Your Honor please, I have no quarrel with it.","start":711.171,"stop":714.752,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what would you suggest should have been Judge Holtzoff's answer to that question?","start":714.752,"stop":719.361,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I think his answer in the circumstances here should have been that is a matter which is not properly before you jurors for your consideration and I will not answer that question.","start":719.361,"stop":733.256,"duration":13.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean -- do I infer from your answer to Justice Brennan that you imply or that you -- you -- we should carry the meaning of what you say that in as much as -- as the amount of the -- in as much as the way in which the judge exercises the discretion other than capital in the sentence that the jury tells particularly.","start":733.256,"stop":762.776,"duration":29.52}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":762.776,"stop":763.347,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He shouldn't tell him what will influence them because that may influence them in bringing in one sentence rather than another?","start":763.347,"stop":769.947,"duration":6.6}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Positively, Your Honor.","start":769.947,"stop":770.481,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your problem?","start":770.481,"stop":771.273,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's my position.","start":771.273,"stop":772.579,"duration":1.31},{"text":"This isn't a case where the jury is charged with the duty of fixing punishment in terms of fixing death or fixing life or fixing a term of years.","start":772.579,"stop":781.479,"duration":8.9},{"text":"This is a case where their sole consideration is to determine guilt or innocence on the one hand and then if they determine that he is guilty, whether or not he should be -- his life should be fought.","start":781.479,"stop":792.943,"duration":11.46},{"text":"If they decide that it shouldn't be, what happens to him in the alternative is not any -- any area in which they can make any consideration.","start":792.943,"stop":802.203,"duration":9.26},{"text":"It's sheer speculation.","start":802.203,"stop":803.748,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in as much as they have that awful power which they have under statute in various mistakes of deciding whether a man should go to his death or not, are they themselves on how they -- how that should be put to them -- are they themselves entitled to consider suppose a jury brought in a verdict saying we find the defendant guilty and we think and we recommend death because of inevitable speech --","start":803.748,"stop":834.392,"duration":30.64}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":834.392,"stop":834.545,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or they shall because we think that you ought not to be alleged inside the community very soon as he will might be but -- what will you say to that kind of a verdict.","start":834.545,"stop":845.879,"duration":11.33},{"text":"Now, that is a --","start":845.879,"stop":847.387,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I think if he --","start":847.387,"stop":847.93,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- illegal verdict?","start":847.93,"stop":849.318,"duration":1.39},{"text":"They gave their reasons from closing, for qualifying the -- or adding to their finding of guilty, the reason for recommending for opposing death as the power --","start":849.318,"stop":865.306,"duration":15.99}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say this, if Your Honor please, that that would be a positive determination of death.","start":865.306,"stop":871.649,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, can't they -- your argument must imply that they cannot get some guidance from the Court for consideration that they may as a perfectly conscientious jury take into account in the privacy of the jury?","start":871.649,"stop":890.759,"duration":19.11}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right Your Honor.","start":890.759,"stop":891.812,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that right?","start":891.812,"stop":892.316,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right sir.","start":892.316,"stop":893.881,"duration":1.56},{"text":"That -- that's my position.","start":893.881,"stop":899.671,"duration":5.79},{"text":"Then the Court --","start":899.671,"stop":900.334,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The answer they got from the judge, what the judge said is something that they could discuss among themselves.","start":900.334,"stop":905.276,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":905.276,"stop":906.696,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the secrecy and privacy of the -- the jury.","start":906.696,"stop":908.494,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":908.494,"stop":909.587,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But your proposition -- you stand on the proposition that the judge has no business to help from defining -- expounding this.","start":909.587,"stop":917.915,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think that --","start":917.915,"stop":919.113,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that right?","start":919.113,"stop":919.769,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"May I take that position, if Your Honor please.","start":919.769,"stop":921.268,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I understand it.","start":921.268,"stop":923.947,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. --","start":923.947,"stop":924.04,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If I may say so, that is the position to take but I just want to know if that's it.","start":924.04,"stop":927.052,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That is my position, if Your Honor please.","start":927.052,"stop":928.813,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant, I -- I gather then that you would probably distinguish in a state statute as I think as the case in some states where the verdict of guilty carries automatically the death penalty unless there's an affirmative recommendation of life imprisonment.","start":928.813,"stop":945.73,"duration":16.92}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":945.73,"stop":945.876,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that it?","start":945.876,"stop":947.118,"duration":1.24},{"text":"And the --","start":947.118,"stop":947.205,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":947.205,"stop":947.325,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- distinction you draw here is that a verdict without the appendage with the death penalty automatically leaves to the judge a determination of what the sentence shall be, is that it?","start":947.325,"stop":961.238,"duration":13.91}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right Your Honor.","start":961.238,"stop":962.538,"duration":1.3},{"text":"In other words, you take the position in -- in the that case that Your Honor cites and I believe that is so in several Ohio --","start":962.538,"stop":968.877,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's some in New Jersey I know.","start":968.877,"stop":970.264,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir, if Your Honor please.","start":970.264,"stop":972.115,"duration":1.85},{"text":"Well, in that particular case, the jury is charged with fixing punishment as a matter of fact in the alternative and they aren't here and another distinction is this, in the wisdom of Congress, what happens to a man if the death penalty isn't imposed at the term of years per years, so they aren't be a meaningfully beginning embedding an area which is fraught with speculation from the very beginning.","start":972.115,"stop":1001.325,"duration":29.21},{"text":"Then they asked for reading of the rape statute and the Court at that time reads the rape statute too and reads the penalty.","start":1001.325,"stop":1013.445,"duration":12.12},{"text":"The Court stated, may the jury have a reading of the D.C. Code, it reads this way, whoever has come knowledge of the female force have been against their will shall be imprisoned for not more than 30 years provided any case of rape the jury may add to their verdict.","start":1013.445,"stop":1026.845,"duration":13.4},{"text":"If he'd be guilty, the words would be death penalty.","start":1026.845,"stop":1029.435,"duration":2.59},{"text":"In which case, punishment shall be death by electrocution provided further that the jury fails to agrees to the punishment, the verdict shall be received and the punishment shall be imprisoned -- imprisonment as provided in this section.","start":1029.435,"stop":1042.637,"duration":13.2},{"text":"Now, as the Court's pleases, I complained of any answer at all to the question.","start":1042.637,"stop":1049.574,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But now, forgive me for this question because I have a great deal of sympathy --","start":1049.574,"stop":1054.523,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1054.523,"stop":1054.804,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- will you forgive my question because I have a great deal of sympathy --","start":1054.804,"stop":1057.963,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly.","start":1057.963,"stop":1058.018,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- from your point of views.","start":1058.018,"stop":1059.668,"duration":1.65},{"text":"It comes from a friendly source.","start":1059.668,"stop":1061.577,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Suppose -- suppose the jury instead of having asked the question they did asked had specifically trained this question, we are honored to tell us whether it is a fact that even though you impose the maximum sentence under the existing parole legislation or whatever an existing laws, it doesn't follow that the defendant will have to serve the maximum sentence.","start":1061.577,"stop":1089.003,"duration":27.43},{"text":"He may serve a much less sentence in view of -- he could behave inside.","start":1089.003,"stop":1094.794,"duration":5.79},{"text":"Couldn't he be allowed to answer that question?","start":1094.794,"stop":1096.315,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1096.315,"stop":1098.156,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Beyond the place, I think the prohibition is against that even in cases where juries have the right to determine punishment, let's say, in lesser offenses like driving while drunk, for instance, where the range of punishment might be from a $100 to $1000 fine and maybe from 30 days to a year in jail.","start":1098.156,"stop":1115.503,"duration":17.35},{"text":"The function of the parole authorities is a distinct -- the executive functions, it's another branch of the Government.","start":1115.503,"stop":1124.732,"duration":9.23},{"text":"And what the -- what -- what -- confidence the Congress has reposed in the wisdom of those persons, people who may be even unborn should not be frustrated or thwarted by somebody anticipating what might be done.","start":1124.732,"stop":1139.993,"duration":15.26},{"text":"The Court properly should say that that is not --","start":1139.993,"stop":1143.211,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"None of your business.","start":1143.211,"stop":1144.237,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"None of your business, Your Honor.","start":1144.237,"stop":1145.388,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On the other hand, the jurors are trying conscientiously to discharge their duty.","start":1145.388,"stop":1150.221,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":1150.221,"stop":1151.126,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They have the power of bringing in a death penalty.","start":1151.126,"stop":1153.128,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":1153.128,"stop":1153.914,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or let's view the -- and they want to know by what consideration.","start":1153.914,"stop":1159.695,"duration":5.78},{"text":"It's not a consideration in harm and reflection should guide them in making that awful judgment.","start":1159.695,"stop":1167.862,"duration":8.17},{"text":"And -- and if they -- I wonder if they merely ask that there isn't a difference between asking a specific fact which can be answered in a specific way in making a little speech like this old speech as to which is calculated as you argue, is calculated to make them realize this fellow may observe law.","start":1167.862,"stop":1188.816,"duration":20.95},{"text":"Isn't there a difference?","start":1188.816,"stop":1191.725,"duration":2.91},{"text":"You were raising a very -- you were raising a very -- to my point of view a very far-reaching question as administration of formal justice.","start":1191.725,"stop":1197.627,"duration":5.9}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor please, I think this.","start":1197.627,"stop":1201.511,"duration":3.88},{"text":"I think that this Court about -- gave the answer to the question a long time ago in the Winston cases which arose in the District of Columbia.","start":1201.511,"stop":1212.817,"duration":11.31},{"text":"And in that -- in those cases, we have that federal statute which said that the penalty for murder in the first degree would be death except if the jury should bring back a verdict of guilty without capital punishment.","start":1212.817,"stop":1226.837,"duration":14.02},{"text":"And then at the first few cases that arose under that statute, a judge told the jury that in -- if they came to any conclusion that these -- that these defendants should not be -- should not receive the death penalty or if they came to the conclusion that the verdict should be without capital punishment that they must find some mitigating circumstances and have some objective credited for him.","start":1226.837,"stop":1255.823,"duration":28.99},{"text":"And this Court said that's not so.","start":1255.823,"stop":1257.912,"duration":2.09},{"text":"This Court uses the term and the total evidence in light of all the evidence.","start":1257.912,"stop":1263.825,"duration":5.91},{"text":"I think that's a cue here, if Your Honor please.","start":1263.825,"stop":1266.532,"duration":2.71},{"text":"I don't believe that punishment in the alternative from the death sentence can be properly construed as evidence in the case.","start":1266.532,"stop":1278.293,"duration":11.76},{"text":"I --","start":1278.293,"stop":1278.379,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Winston -- the Winston case really was a strong into measuring or at least, hence in a murder case anything that the trial court judge said that to my point of view is strong and important, anything than -- everything that resorts at great length.","start":1278.379,"stop":1293.49,"duration":15.11},{"text":"But in the Winston case, this Court said in effect, and if I may say, just quite right to -- but the judge practically told them, \"You ought to bring a death sentence unless you got a good reason for not doing so.\"","start":1293.49,"stop":1305.314,"duration":11.82},{"text":"That -- that will be effectuating this.","start":1305.314,"stop":1306.718,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1306.718,"stop":1308.224,"duration":1.51},{"text":"If Your Honor please --","start":1308.224,"stop":1308.56,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If you can't do that, this isn't quite right, this isn't that the crime.","start":1308.56,"stop":1314.3,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor please, I have the -- I take the position that it was then.","start":1314.3,"stop":1318.563,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That the effect was the same.","start":1318.563,"stop":1320.441,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"The effect was the same, particularly, in the light of these circumstances, if Your Honor please.","start":1320.441,"stop":1326.041,"duration":5.6},{"text":"If not death, then there was no life imprisonment that was 30 years.","start":1326.041,"stop":1331.372,"duration":5.33},{"text":"And then with the imposition of 30 years, the indeterminate sentence law is no part of the statute on rape.","start":1331.372,"stop":1338.185,"duration":6.81},{"text":"It's a separate part of the code, and then when Judge Holtzoff mentioned the indeterminate sentence law and then went to the point of the Parole Board having the authority to determine that the end of the minimum period it need not to serve anymore unless they see -- was in effect emphasizing.","start":1338.185,"stop":1360.115,"duration":21.93},{"text":"Now, the possibilities and probabilities that this young -- young man would be out in no time, so that was the effect of it that they could not be escaped and that's why I -- I said at one point that the arrow was sort of progressive arrow.","start":1360.115,"stop":1375.869,"duration":15.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What you really think is that they cut there deep into the whole conception went out to the jury, what you really think is that the contradiction or deny what I've put to you earlier, can't they get some rational guidance from the judges to how they should exercise, what is their power maybe to them before the death sentence that what you're really saying is this had better be lasting all in what you will, the feeling, the hunch, the -- the -- some total human feeling of these 12 people, men and women whether this fellowship goes to a death or not.","start":1375.869,"stop":1411.251,"duration":35.38}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1411.251,"stop":1411.702,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You better not have any inclusion of any kind of enlightenment from the Court on that subject.","start":1411.702,"stop":1415.626,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1415.626,"stop":1416.57,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant.","start":1416.57,"stop":1417.311,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"To the purpose.","start":1417.311,"stop":1418.167,"duration":0.86},{"text":"Excuse me, sir.","start":1418.167,"stop":1419.255,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it not really get down to this whether the question -- the question number two with 107 of the record was proper to be answered in any circumstances?","start":1419.255,"stop":1436.915,"duration":17.66},{"text":"Do you say that if it was to be answered at all that Judge Holtzoff could have done better or anyone else than he did?","start":1436.915,"stop":1447.462,"duration":10.55}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1447.462,"stop":1449.035,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"If it was to be answered at all, you think it could have been answered better than Judge Holtzoff did answer?","start":1449.035,"stop":1455.931,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1455.931,"stop":1456.697,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You do?","start":1456.697,"stop":1457.764,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I assert that this is fiduciary and I think it shouldn't have been answered at all.","start":1457.764,"stop":1461.798,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"It shouldn't have been asked?","start":1461.798,"stop":1463.297,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"It shouldn't have been asked either, if Your Honor please.","start":1463.297,"stop":1465.989,"duration":2.69},{"text":"It shouldn't have been answered at all and the only federal cases we had Your Honor, the Lovely versus United States.","start":1465.989,"stop":1472.932,"duration":6.94},{"text":"Now, in the Lovely case, it's true that Judge Parker pointed out or it was pointed out by someone that this answer that -- that the Court's charge relative to the parole possibilities on a life term were -- were gratuitously offered by the Court and not in response to an inquiry.","start":1472.932,"stop":1498.505,"duration":25.57},{"text":"But the language of Judge Parker was to this effect.","start":1498.505,"stop":1501.301,"duration":2.8},{"text":"That's something with which the jury has nothing to do.","start":1501.301,"stop":1504.018,"duration":2.72},{"text":"I think that's --","start":1504.018,"stop":1504.152,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- that thing I will answer.","start":1504.152,"stop":1507.025,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1507.025,"stop":1507.546,"duration":0.52},{"text":"Now, specifically as to your question about Judge Holtzoff's correctness or incorrectness in answer to the question, it seems to me, if Your Honor please, that in the circumstances of this case and in the light of the law which had governs in the District of Columbia, death isn't imposed, that if he answered at all, his answer should have been confined to a straight unequivocal, unelaborated upon no.","start":1507.546,"stop":1539.276,"duration":31.73},{"text":"I'm saying this that when he went beyond and gave the jury the range of what might happen to this man, they didn't asked for that.","start":1539.276,"stop":1550.714,"duration":11.44},{"text":"And the extent to which he went almost forward on advocacy, he came to the point where he's injecting himself into that jury room.","start":1550.714,"stop":1560.311,"duration":9.6},{"text":"The emphasis upon the possibilities that at the end of 10 years, this man would be in the street.","start":1560.311,"stop":1565.491,"duration":5.18},{"text":"The jury didn't ask for that, if Your Honor please, and I think that it would (Inaudible) to -- to tell her that.","start":1565.491,"stop":1570.211,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm a -- I'm a little troubled.","start":1570.211,"stop":1572.257,"duration":2.05},{"text":"Didn't the jury ask the question that the -- on -- in quote on top of page 107?","start":1572.257,"stop":1578.331,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Can we, the jury be assured that --","start":1578.331,"stop":1579.712,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't they ask that?","start":1579.712,"stop":1582.247,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"They asked --","start":1582.247,"stop":1582.391,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't that there a question?","start":1582.391,"stop":1584.248,"duration":1.86},{"text":"Was there not that question?","start":1584.248,"stop":1585.947,"duration":1.7},{"text":"Did they not put those very words to the judgment?","start":1585.947,"stop":1589.4,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"The jury?","start":1589.4,"stop":1590.056,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The jury, isn't it?","start":1590.056,"stop":1591.163,"duration":1.11},{"text":"Under the jury verdict?","start":1591.163,"stop":1592.023,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1592.023,"stop":1592.446,"duration":0.42},{"text":"Yes, sir, that's -- that's what they asked.","start":1592.446,"stop":1593.485,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was an evidence covered by your answer to Justice Whittaker that the jury didn't ask for that?","start":1593.485,"stop":1598.108,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't mean that.","start":1598.108,"stop":1598.451,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I misunderstood you.","start":1598.451,"stop":1599.664,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean that, if Your Honor please.","start":1599.664,"stop":1601.689,"duration":2.03},{"text":"The jury was not asking about alternative sentences.","start":1601.689,"stop":1608.238,"duration":6.55},{"text":"They were asking about an assurance of something that didn't exist.","start":1608.238,"stop":1612.977,"duration":4.74},{"text":"They were asking the --","start":1612.977,"stop":1614.603,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the evidence, supposing he answered, just said no.","start":1614.603,"stop":1617.105,"duration":2.5},{"text":"Can we be -- the jury be assured defendant legally be imprisoned for the remainder of his natural life?","start":1617.105,"stop":1621.919,"duration":4.81},{"text":"Supposing he'd said no, you would have the same -- you would object to that, wouldn't you?","start":1621.919,"stop":1624.998,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I was complained about that, if Your Honor please.","start":1624.998,"stop":1626.095,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, you complained but this is different.","start":1626.095,"stop":1627.549,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"This is different.","start":1627.549,"stop":1628.139,"duration":0.59},{"text":"This is worse.","start":1628.139,"stop":1628.638,"duration":0.5},{"text":"This is aggravated.","start":1628.638,"stop":1630.924,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the answer which the judge gave technically are not -- not with reference to your problem.","start":1630.924,"stop":1635.856,"duration":4.93},{"text":"Is it technically correct --","start":1635.856,"stop":1637.705,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"It is but --","start":1637.705,"stop":1638.174,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at the situation of the law?","start":1638.174,"stop":1639.369,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right but it's not responsive, if Your Honor please.","start":1639.369,"stop":1641.338,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand it.","start":1641.338,"stop":1642.226,"duration":0.89},{"text":"But I mean this is technically correct.","start":1642.226,"stop":1643.411,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1643.411,"stop":1644.212,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, if it was technically wrong, I wouldn't bother along with it.","start":1644.212,"stop":1647.266,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":1647.266,"stop":1648.449,"duration":1.18},{"text":"It would technically be correct, if Your Honor please.","start":1648.449,"stop":1650.32,"duration":1.87},{"text":"As far as it went, I'm saying that he shouldn't have gone as far as he did.","start":1650.32,"stop":1653.196,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In that I follow you.","start":1653.196,"stop":1660.169,"duration":6.97}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, some cases have --","start":1660.169,"stop":1667.295,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I -- except one more thing.","start":1667.295,"stop":1668.823,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1668.823,"stop":1668.97,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose -- suppose one should find that he -- that one should agree with you speaking of consequences, it would have to go back for -- it wasn't tried, wasn't it?","start":1668.97,"stop":1685.108,"duration":16.14}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1685.108,"stop":1685.943,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He couldn't impose the sentence, of course, and the old jury couldn't be called back.","start":1685.943,"stop":1690.649,"duration":4.71},{"text":"And it -- well, could it -- I don't know what do you suggest or either by you or by the Government that could -- that the case suddenly sends back to vacate the death sentence and impose the life sentence.","start":1690.649,"stop":1704.44,"duration":13.79},{"text":"I don't know what the Government (Inaudible)","start":1704.44,"stop":1706.061,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I -- I would want to venture to the answer on that.","start":1706.061,"stop":1708.417,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose one might have to face that question if one agreed with you, wouldn't one?","start":1708.417,"stop":1714.553,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":1714.553,"stop":1716.424,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the only thing that bothers me about that, Mr. Bryant.","start":1716.424,"stop":1719.506,"duration":3.08},{"text":"If I understand your position, it's a jury determination and I suppose is an integral part of the judgment of conviction that the death sentence should be imposed, isn't it here?","start":1719.506,"stop":1735.396,"duration":15.89}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"As it is now, yes, Your Honor.","start":1735.396,"stop":1737.347,"duration":1.95},{"text":"The death sentence has become a part of the verdict.","start":1737.347,"stop":1740.327,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, how -- how can any but the jury (Voice Overlap) --","start":1740.327,"stop":1744.778,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I participate some difficulty in that area, Your Honor.","start":1744.778,"stop":1747.799,"duration":3.02},{"text":"I -- I can understand what's troubling you.","start":1747.799,"stop":1750.972,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except that's a difficult question for me was when I -- it doesn't seem irrational to me to say the death sentence was improperly imposed?","start":1750.972,"stop":1758.817,"duration":7.85},{"text":"The death sentence is vacated to the finding of guilty that you do the best you can.(Voice Overlap) --","start":1758.817,"stop":1767.898,"duration":9.08}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1767.898,"stop":1768.709,"duration":0.81},{"text":"In the finding of guilty, I don't think there's any equivocation about that.","start":1768.709,"stop":1771.083,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If they said nothing that the jury brought in guilty then -- then it wouldn't be death?","start":1771.083,"stop":1775.393,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1775.393,"stop":1776.12,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I noticed --","start":1776.12,"stop":1776.273,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant, Oh, pardon me, just go right ahead.","start":1776.273,"stop":1780.665,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, sir.","start":1780.665,"stop":1781.93,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I noticed that the last question that the jury asked was, \"May the jury have a reading of the D.C. Code rewrite?\"","start":1781.93,"stop":1790.823,"duration":8.89},{"text":"That was one of their questions.","start":1790.823,"stop":1792.069,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1792.069,"stop":1793.493,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And then the Court proceeded to read the statute.","start":1793.493,"stop":1796.413,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1796.413,"stop":1797.101,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, did he say anything more in his preliminary explanation than was contained in the reading of the statute?","start":1797.101,"stop":1806.631,"duration":9.53}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"In the -- you mean there is no charge.","start":1806.631,"stop":1808.696,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The part that we've been talking about.","start":1808.696,"stop":1810.257,"duration":1.56},{"text":"Now, the part on his -- it's a part of his answer to the jury's earlier question that you objected to.","start":1810.257,"stop":1816.551,"duration":6.29},{"text":"That simply is summarization of the statute, isn't it?","start":1816.551,"stop":1819.611,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's right, if Your Honor please.","start":1819.611,"stop":1820.823,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, do you object to the view -- supposing the Court had said, \"I will not answer your question except to say that I -- to read you the statute in response to your last question,\" would you -- objected to that?","start":1820.823,"stop":1833.659,"duration":12.84}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, if he read the -- the statute as he did in his original charge.","start":1833.659,"stop":1839.347,"duration":5.69},{"text":"The safe way that judges usually adopt is to say I've already instructed you on that matter and that's the end of it.","start":1839.347,"stop":1845.593,"duration":6.25},{"text":"If he had said no and then read the statute without regard to the punishment, I would have been satisfied.","start":1845.593,"stop":1853.268,"duration":7.67},{"text":"But I don't think that that was an area for the jury to be concerned with whether or not he got 30 years or 10 to 30 or 9 to 27.","start":1853.268,"stop":1861.702,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant, I suppose implicit in your argument is the -- is the fact that the colloquy of this kind is -- there's a vise in it because it -- it's likely to produce a compromised verdict and that that being true, any -- any verdict that -- that was brought about as a result of such a colloquy is subject to the -- the criticism that it might be -- it might be a compromised verdict.","start":1861.702,"stop":1895.325,"duration":33.62}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so, if Your Honor please.","start":1895.325,"stop":1898.646,"duration":3.32},{"text":"That's my position.","start":1898.646,"stop":1899.619,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, excuse me, Mr. Bryant, I don't follow that.","start":1899.619,"stop":1902.333,"duration":2.71},{"text":"How could there be a compromised verdict?","start":1902.333,"stop":1903.903,"duration":1.57},{"text":"As I understand it, unless unanimously they attach the death penalty to the verdict, automatically he gets only imprisonment.","start":1903.903,"stop":1912.652,"duration":8.75}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1912.652,"stop":1912.785,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There couldn't be a compromise.","start":1912.785,"stop":1914.068,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1914.068,"stop":1914.81,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It didn't -- it didn't result in a compromise.","start":1914.81,"stop":1916.537,"duration":1.73},{"text":"I gather your position is that it was an intrusion in the sense that it led the jury unanimously to the finding of death penalty that -- but for what he said that -- at least there may have been a disagreement upon in which he fairly could not have had more than imprisonment, isn't that it?","start":1916.537,"stop":1933.384,"duration":16.85}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't mean compromise in those terms, if Your Honor please.","start":1933.384,"stop":1937.181,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I was talking about compromise in this -- in this sense.","start":1937.181,"stop":1941.512,"duration":4.33},{"text":"Some of the jurors might have been for the death penalty.","start":1941.512,"stop":1944.403,"duration":2.89},{"text":"Some of them might have been for -- for life imprisonment.","start":1944.403,"stop":1948.36,"duration":3.96},{"text":"And -- and those who were for the death penalty might have said, \"Well, if we could -- if we could be sure that he would stay in jail for the rest of his life, we will -- we would find him guilty of -- of the offense punishable less than death.","start":1948.36,"stop":1966.181,"duration":17.82},{"text":"But unless we can be assured of that fact, we will go with the other group.\"","start":1966.181,"stop":1971.52,"duration":5.34}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1971.52,"stop":1972.528,"duration":1.01},{"text":"That's a deal so to speak.","start":1972.528,"stop":1973.849,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a deal, it's a compromise.","start":1973.849,"stop":1974.146,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean -- in fact the jury say it's -- it's --","start":1974.146,"stop":1975.912,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In that sense --","start":1975.912,"stop":1976.666,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1976.666,"stop":1977.058,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's -- that's the sense I used to deal.","start":1977.058,"stop":1978.473,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1978.473,"stop":1979.256,"duration":0.78},{"text":"And I think --","start":1979.256,"stop":1979.386,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It may go even further than that.","start":1979.386,"stop":1981.495,"duration":2.11},{"text":"They go even further than that.","start":1981.495,"stop":1982.78,"duration":1.29},{"text":"One doesn't have to know much about juries to know that there may be jurors on that jury who would say, \"I'm ready to find him guilty if he isn't sentenced to death.\"","start":1982.78,"stop":1993.115,"duration":10.34}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1993.115,"stop":1993.806,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"\"But I'd hold out against the verdict of guilty.\"","start":1993.806,"stop":1998.07,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1998.07,"stop":1998.254,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was to insist on technically trying there is alternative, he may be switched over from voting for acquittal to guilt?","start":1998.254,"stop":2004.523,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2004.523,"stop":2004.723,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not an unknown.","start":2004.723,"stop":2008.349,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"So that this -- this I think this -- I think in specific, the answer to your question Your Honor that -- that a jury in arriving in the determination is great as this.","start":2008.349,"stop":2017.403,"duration":9.05},{"text":"It shouldn't impose the death penalty in terms of negative reaction.","start":2017.403,"stop":2021.842,"duration":4.44},{"text":"In other words, the death penalty should reflect the heinousness of the crime in certain things in which it was committed and not any disapproval of anything that the Congress in its wisdom has adopted as alternative.","start":2021.842,"stop":2035.653,"duration":13.81},{"text":"If that isn't their business, strictly isn't their business to say this to them.","start":2035.653,"stop":2040.553,"duration":4.9},{"text":"If it would be improper -- if it were improper -- we'll put another way I should say that the Court's original charge relative to the law and the jury response was the extent to which they should have been informed.","start":2040.553,"stop":2056.806,"duration":16.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, what was done is an official, improper -- if that's a good English, intrusion under the function of the jury which vitiates because of its prejudice to the verdict of death.","start":2056.806,"stop":2070.562,"duration":13.76}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, if Your Honor please.","start":2070.562,"stop":2071.882,"duration":1.32},{"text":"I think --","start":2071.882,"stop":2074.382,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I understood you to say that you objected to the answer that the Court gave to this in -- but I don't find that.","start":2074.382,"stop":2081.936,"duration":7.55},{"text":"Where is it?","start":2081.936,"stop":2083.092,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I -- if Your Honor please, I didn't -- I didn't -- I don't think I said that as to the objective of the introduction of the evidence.","start":2083.092,"stop":2089.938,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I misunderstood you.","start":2089.938,"stop":2090.245,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"But as to the --","start":2090.245,"stop":2092.076,"duration":1.83},{"text":"And if I did say that, I don't mean that.","start":2092.076,"stop":2094.623,"duration":2.55},{"text":"But I did make it the basis for -- in a motion for a new trial, if Your Honor please.","start":2094.623,"stop":2098.857,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When -- when the questions first came in and as the record says, I want to show you gentlemen, meaning counsel --","start":2098.857,"stop":2105.219,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2105.219,"stop":2105.784,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a note that I received from the jury.","start":2105.784,"stop":2107.918,"duration":2.13},{"text":"I think as to the question they asked on number two.","start":2107.918,"stop":2112.238,"duration":4.32},{"text":"I shall have to say that I cannot give them any such assurance, Mr. McLaughlin, that's the District Attorney.","start":2112.238,"stop":2117.877,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2117.877,"stop":2118.75,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right and nothing further appears.","start":2118.75,"stop":2121.24,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2121.24,"stop":2122.461,"duration":1.22},{"text":"Well, if Your Honor please, I might say this.","start":2122.461,"stop":2126.38,"duration":3.92},{"text":"That I was in an unfamiliar situation at that point and I said nothing as the record reflects.","start":2126.38,"stop":2137.367,"duration":10.99},{"text":"But I assure Your Honot that had I had any idea that the judge is going to say what he did say, I would have just objected spontaneously.","start":2137.367,"stop":2150.333,"duration":12.97},{"text":"He said, I'm going to tell him, I can give him the no, the answer is no.","start":2150.333,"stop":2153.701,"duration":3.37},{"text":"I can give no such assurance.","start":2153.701,"stop":2155.965,"duration":2.26},{"text":"I had in my mind at that time that that wasn't a proper thing to do.","start":2155.965,"stop":2160.683,"duration":4.72},{"text":"But certainly if I had any idea in the world --","start":2160.683,"stop":2162.592,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he gave but you didn't say anything?","start":2162.592,"stop":2165.317,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor please, I -- I felt helpless under the --","start":2165.317,"stop":2167.786,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not saying that you're bound by that --","start":2167.786,"stop":2169.751,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":2169.751,"stop":2170.115,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I'm just trying to find out.","start":2170.115,"stop":2171.441,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought about that to some extent but I can imagine nothing that could have been done in those circumstances that could have protected -- that could have obviated it or at least affected it.","start":2171.441,"stop":2181.12,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the jury's reaction but it might have put your record in a little better position?","start":2181.12,"stop":2184.656,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, I agree.","start":2184.656,"stop":2188.822,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant, are you going to find time to discuss the first question, the question of the detention?","start":2188.822,"stop":2195.55,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, if Your Honor please, I would like to complement.","start":2195.55,"stop":2199.083,"duration":3.53},{"text":"If Your Honor please, I think that the confessions in this case fall within the prohibitions of the McNabb doctrine for this reason.","start":2199.083,"stop":2207.333,"duration":8.25},{"text":"At the time this man was taken to the headquarters building in question, he was literally taken down a car on one side across the street for 15 or so judges of the District Court and nine of the Court of Appeals and the United States Commissioner, the width of the street.","start":2207.333,"stop":2223.32,"duration":15.99},{"text":"A block away was the Municipal Court for the District of Columbia, all of the judges on which are empowered to act as committee magistrates.","start":2223.32,"stop":2231.965,"duration":8.64},{"text":"Now, the delay between time of arrest and the time that the Commissioner was sought was not a delay which arose out of expensive circumstances or which the police had no control, it was a delay which was chosen by the police for the purpose of interrogation.","start":2231.965,"stop":2247.495,"duration":15.53},{"text":"And I think, if Your Honor pleases, that the McNabb and Upshaw mean what I'm certain that the Court have said that -- that they mean and who file was to be observed at all that the delay in this particular case were such as to invalidate the confessions.","start":2247.495,"stop":2264.418,"duration":16.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You said that the delay was chosen.","start":2264.418,"stop":2266.511,"duration":2.09},{"text":"It was designed --","start":2266.511,"stop":2266.642,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Delay was chosen.","start":2266.642,"stop":2268.098,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The design delay.","start":2268.098,"stop":2269.236,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":2269.236,"stop":2269.637,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you please refer us or quickly state what the evidence in the record is for that statement?","start":2269.637,"stop":2275.286,"duration":5.65},{"text":"What is the --","start":2275.286,"stop":2276.708,"duration":1.42},{"text":"On what do you based that statement?","start":2276.708,"stop":2278.729,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I had based that statement, if Your Honor please, on the fact that on -- at -- in the record on page 52, I believe.","start":2278.729,"stop":2288.614,"duration":9.89},{"text":"The police -- I am reading down near the -- well, the third question from the bottom.","start":2288.614,"stop":2306.837,"duration":18.22},{"text":"If Your Honor please.","start":2306.837,"stop":2308.28,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"On what page?","start":2308.28,"stop":2308.994,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 52 of the record where the -- Mr. McLaughlin said, \"We're calling your attention after the defendant stated to you that he'd made a verbal statement.","start":2308.994,"stop":2317.418,"duration":8.42},{"text":"You stated he made a verbal statement.","start":2317.418,"stop":2319.101,"duration":1.68},{"text":"Was there any attempt at that time to get in touch with the United States Commissioner?\"","start":2319.101,"stop":2322.689,"duration":3.59},{"text":"Answer, “Yes, sir.","start":2322.689,"stop":2323.65,"duration":0.96},{"text":"Sergeant Elliot made a call to the home of the United States Commissioner.","start":2323.65,"stop":2327.31,"duration":3.66},{"text":"Commissioner was unavailable.\"","start":2327.31,"stop":2328.944,"duration":1.63},{"text":"\"And that was approximately what time?\"","start":2328.944,"stop":2330.635,"duration":1.69},{"text":"\"It was some time after 10 o'clock.\"","start":2330.635,"stop":2332.866,"duration":2.23},{"text":"Now, I say that the record reflects that this was a matter of choice for this reason, that he was interrogated then they waited for the lie detector man to come to interrogate him some more.","start":2332.866,"stop":2348.227,"duration":15.36},{"text":"There was absolutely no reason indicated by the record why he should not have been arraigned.","start":2348.227,"stop":2354.318,"duration":6.09},{"text":"I say that a test is not the time that --","start":2354.318,"stop":2356.39,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what time was he arrested?","start":2356.39,"stop":2358.067,"duration":1.68},{"text":"When was he convicted?","start":2358.067,"stop":2358.814,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"He was arrested about 2:30 and arrived at the police headquarters, if Your Honor please, which was across the street from these people and about 3 o'clock, shortly before 3 o'clock.","start":2358.814,"stop":2368.023,"duration":9.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the Commissioner --","start":2368.023,"stop":2369.134,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commissioner --","start":2369.134,"stop":2369.689,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap), what's the geography of the Commissioner's home?","start":2369.689,"stop":2372.675,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"These buildings, if Your Honor please, are directly across the street one from the other directly across the street.","start":2372.675,"stop":2380.941,"duration":8.27},{"text":"The interrogation took place on the fourth floor of this building over here.","start":2380.941,"stop":2385.444,"duration":4.5},{"text":"In third, it seems to be South and Northwest.","start":2385.444,"stop":2388.425,"duration":2.98},{"text":"The United States Commissioner's office is in the Northwest corner of the New United States District Court building, a third is on market-based, and coincidentally, it was about the closest office to the police headquarters.","start":2388.425,"stop":2407.841,"duration":19.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the Commissioner that we know -- whether the commissioner sitting in his office, is he there particularly available?","start":2407.841,"stop":2416.447,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor please, I don't know what he was --","start":2416.447,"stop":2419.326,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No --","start":2419.326,"stop":2419.466,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"The assumption is that during the business hours that he was.","start":2419.466,"stop":2423.474,"duration":4.01},{"text":"We know --","start":2423.474,"stop":2423.553,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The position of the district have a good deal of business or that he -- did he get a full time job","start":2423.553,"stop":2428.852,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"He has full time job, if Your Honor please, on a yearly salary.","start":2428.852,"stop":2432.011,"duration":3.16},{"text":"And I'll say that my experience both as with the commissioner, I spent a lot of time with him that he was aware of the fact that he should be on duty at least until the judges were on duty about 4:30.","start":2432.011,"stop":2447.831,"duration":15.82},{"text":"I know that that was a fact that that was the practice there.","start":2447.831,"stop":2452.214,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if he's on a full time on a yearly salary --","start":2452.214,"stop":2455.582,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"About 95 --","start":2455.582,"stop":2455.988,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know nothing about this but I should think Washington is big enough to have a commissioner who's there on full time?","start":2455.988,"stop":2460.573,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":2460.573,"stop":2461.381,"duration":0.81},{"text":"His salary was $9500.","start":2461.381,"stop":2463.083,"duration":1.7},{"text":"I think he was furnished a staff.","start":2463.083,"stop":2465.063,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you suggest that he should be presumably there until 4:30 anyhow?","start":2465.063,"stop":2468.745,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh certainly.","start":2468.745,"stop":2469.375,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not a wild assumption, is it?","start":2469.375,"stop":2471.196,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Not -- not a wild assumption.","start":2471.196,"stop":2472.314,"duration":1.12},{"text":"I think that at least they should have attempted to get in touch with him in his office some time before 4:30 rather than waiting until after 10.","start":2472.314,"stop":2478.441,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the exact time when -- when this defendant was brought into police headquarters?","start":2478.441,"stop":2483.409,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"3 o'clock, if Your Honor please.","start":2483.409,"stop":2484.393,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"3 o'clock?","start":2484.393,"stop":2484.982,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"3 o'clock.","start":2484.982,"stop":2486.639,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But they also have taken him, did you say, to the municipal judges?","start":2486.639,"stop":2490.419,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they could have taken him to the municipal -- municipal judges who I know are in session until after 4 o'clock.","start":2490.419,"stop":2498.145,"duration":7.73},{"text":"They could have taken him to any one of the District Court judges, there's always one on duty at least until the time.","start":2498.145,"stop":2502.486,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How many district judges are there?","start":2502.486,"stop":2503.933,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":2503.933,"stop":2504.557,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How many district judges are there at the district?","start":2504.557,"stop":2506.373,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"There are 13.","start":2506.373,"stop":2507.658,"duration":1.28},{"text":"There were 13 of --","start":2507.658,"stop":2508.294,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They're all in that building over there?","start":2508.294,"stop":2509.656,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"All in that building, the United States Courthouse, nine of the Court of Appeals judges and 13 district judges and the United States Commissioner.","start":2509.656,"stop":2515.995,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are -- are defendants ever taken before at the District Court arraigned?","start":2515.995,"stop":2521.556,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2521.556,"stop":2521.732,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The District Court's -- the district judges take arraignments --","start":2521.732,"stop":2524.439,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, I've done it, if Your Honor please, personally for the very purpose of -- of eliminating this contention and I would say this that the municipal court judges are utilized fully as much as the United States Commissioner.","start":2524.439,"stop":2536.344,"duration":11.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean you can break in toward a particular case?","start":2536.344,"stop":2540.056,"duration":3.71},{"text":"I mean there's an arrest at 3 o'clock and a conscientious district attorney could take him to even the Commissioner or he isn't, for some reason, there or busy, you could take him to the municipal court as such --","start":2540.056,"stop":2549.45,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, sir.","start":2549.45,"stop":2550.49,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and say, “Your Honor, I have a case.\"","start":2550.49,"stop":2552.156,"duration":1.67},{"text":"Is that all right?","start":2552.156,"stop":2552.621,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2552.621,"stop":2553.74,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No trouble about that?","start":2553.74,"stop":2555.083,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"No trouble and the municipal court judges will make themselves available.","start":2555.083,"stop":2558.326,"duration":3.24},{"text":"They will wait for you, late in the evenings, sometimes after 5:00.","start":2558.326,"stop":2562.136,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How many municipal court judges are there?","start":2562.136,"stop":2564.404,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"There are 11, if Your Honor please.","start":2564.404,"stop":2571.278,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"One more question, Mr. Bryant.","start":2571.278,"stop":2572.654,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2572.654,"stop":2573.535,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you -- on this Court -- on this aspect of your case, unlawful illegal detention, the McNabb one part.","start":2573.535,"stop":2581.409,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2581.409,"stop":2582.234,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you properly, technically preserve your -- your claim of error as to that?","start":2582.234,"stop":2588.533,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor please, I think I did throughout.","start":2588.533,"stop":2592.076,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Raise it early?","start":2592.076,"stop":2593.328,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I raised it early, yes, sir.","start":2593.328,"stop":2596.246,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When?","start":2596.246,"stop":2596.529,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"When Mr. -- at that trial court when Mr. McLaughlin mentioned to the Court that this is a confession case, if Your Honor pleases.","start":2596.529,"stop":2604.994,"duration":8.47},{"text":"And I was --","start":2604.994,"stop":2608.817,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you point to the place in the record where you first did, Mr. Bryant, without too much trouble or -- don't use your time doing it now if you can.","start":2608.817,"stop":2615.823,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I can't.","start":2615.823,"stop":2617.161,"duration":1.34},{"text":"I need to put my finger --","start":2617.161,"stop":2618.045,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's all right.","start":2618.045,"stop":2618.31,"duration":0.26},{"text":"I get it, you have provided it.","start":2618.31,"stop":2618.791,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I will need to put my finger on --","start":2618.791,"stop":2620.149,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Has the Government challenged the fact as to whether you did bring it to the attention of the Court?","start":2620.149,"stop":2624.899,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2624.899,"stop":2626.098,"duration":1.2},{"text":"They haven't challenged it, Your Honor.","start":2626.098,"stop":2627.014,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Have they challenged the other question?","start":2627.014,"stop":2628.816,"duration":1.8},{"text":"Have they said, you haven't -- the question that Justice Harlan put that you did not object to the answer by the trial judge?","start":2628.816,"stop":2636.427,"duration":7.61},{"text":"Did the Government raise that?","start":2636.427,"stop":2637.473,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Some references made within the Government's brief but not a formal challenge, I believe in the footnote --","start":2637.473,"stop":2642.165,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2642.165,"stop":2642.415,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if Your Honor please.","start":2642.415,"stop":2643.465,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"Until after the lie detector test, did they have enough to arraign him for?","start":2643.465,"stop":2650.431,"duration":6.97}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if Your Honor please, they had enough to arraign him when they arrested him.","start":2650.431,"stop":2655.593,"duration":5.16},{"text":"Now, if Your Honor means if did they have enough for the commissioner to hold him, I think it's a different question.","start":2655.593,"stop":2661.287,"duration":5.69},{"text":"I think that purposes of arraignment is to determine whether or not there's enough to hold him.","start":2661.287,"stop":2665.76,"duration":4.47},{"text":"I don't think the police -- that was the Upshaw rape case.","start":2665.76,"stop":2668.557,"duration":2.8},{"text":"The police said it didn't they take him there because we didn't have enough for the commission at a holding and that was the fact here, so that --","start":2668.557,"stop":2675.645,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what you mean by saying the failure to arraign was designed in order to enable him to get the evidence.","start":2675.645,"stop":2681.258,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, the sole purpose of the delay.","start":2681.258,"stop":2684.212,"duration":2.95},{"text":"And I say to Your Honor that when the Commissioner is available and the arresting authority has failed to take advantage of his availability for the purpose of arraigning, then that detention is illegal and --","start":2684.212,"stop":2695.098,"duration":10.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand the Government doesn't argue there as I -- as I gather from their brief.","start":2695.098,"stop":2700.226,"duration":5.13},{"text":"What they say is, they had him there along with two others investigating a crime?","start":2700.226,"stop":2704.772,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2704.772,"stop":2705.77,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"There was enough -- enough evidence to get anybody?","start":2705.77,"stop":2708.103,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":2708.103,"stop":2709.041,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And that they claim they had a right to investigate and interrogate witnesses and they recommend an injustice to him to arraign him or charge him with the murder when they didn't have the evidence?","start":2709.041,"stop":2720.82,"duration":11.78}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2720.82,"stop":2721.669,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Your issue is drawn on whether that's a sufficient reasoning.","start":2721.669,"stop":2724.493,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think there's any reason, if Your Honor please.","start":2724.493,"stop":2727.063,"duration":2.57},{"text":"And when the -- when --","start":2727.063,"stop":2727.471,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But I mean that that's the argument between --","start":2727.471,"stop":2729.13,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the argument of the Government.","start":2729.13,"stop":2730.572,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not read in the arguments and in the brief of the Government, any challenge to the fact.","start":2730.572,"stop":2735.264,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":2735.264,"stop":2735.849,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But he could have been taken to a commissioner much earlier?","start":2735.849,"stop":2739.263,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they are saying this that the reasons that they didn't take him were logical reasons and made the delay necessary.","start":2739.263,"stop":2747.227,"duration":7.96},{"text":"I say to Your Honor that the only necessary delay is the delay in which the police are not in the position of choosing.","start":2747.227,"stop":2752.387,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying is that if there is cause for arrest, there must some cause for arrest and there is the question of -- is that sufficient cause for detention?","start":2752.387,"stop":2762.294,"duration":9.91}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":2762.294,"stop":2763.261,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And soon as the -- there is cause for arrest, to justify the arrest, he should be brought before a magistrate and then the Government could say, \"Your Honor, we want this witness at all events detained until we can ascertain if anybody is guilty of a crime.\"","start":2763.261,"stop":2779.059,"duration":15.8},{"text":"At least sufficient evidence to prosecute him and further whether there is sufficient evidence to -- to prosecute these fellows --","start":2779.059,"stop":2785.761,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"We ask the --","start":2785.761,"stop":2785.946,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and therefore, we want him detained.","start":2785.946,"stop":2787.866,"duration":1.92},{"text":"But you were saying, the essence of the McNabb rule is that you can't hold him until you find out whether you've got enough on the fellow.","start":2787.866,"stop":2794.741,"duration":6.88},{"text":"That's your position.","start":2794.741,"stop":2795.901,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, I say that that's police's position.","start":2795.901,"stop":2798.243,"duration":2.34},{"text":"That's not mine --","start":2798.243,"stop":2798.329,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm saying that you say you reject -- you -- you challenge that.","start":2798.329,"stop":2801.432,"duration":3.1},{"text":"That's right, I challenge that.","start":2801.432,"stop":2802.1,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the whole point.","start":2802.1,"stop":2803.021,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":2803.021,"stop":2803.409,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That you can't just arrest a fellow with sufficient expectation or suspicion or -- or feeling, knowledge, probable cause to arrest him and then keep him there until you get out of him what you want and make out a case.","start":2803.409,"stop":2816.781,"duration":13.37},{"text":"That's your case, isn't it?","start":2816.781,"stop":2817.526,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":2817.526,"stop":2818.972,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":2818.972,"stop":2822.451,"duration":3.48}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 01, 1957 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13226","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant, had you concluded your opening remarks?","start":0,"stop":7.25,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"You Honor --","start":7.25,"stop":7.28,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Had you --","start":7.28,"stop":7.92,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"-- please I haven't, I believe --","start":7.92,"stop":9.21,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":9.21,"stop":9.23,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"-- there's about 13 more minutes --","start":9.23,"stop":10.72,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, you may have some more time.","start":10.72,"stop":12.19,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":12.19,"stop":12.85,"duration":0.66},{"text":"Two or three to just one question, and reserve the rest of the time for rebuttal.","start":12.85,"stop":16.84,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":16.84,"stop":18.23,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"In reference particularly to the admission of the evidence which was obtained pursuant to the so-called consent to service.","start":18.23,"stop":26.54,"duration":8.31},{"text":"I believe that that evidence was illegally seized for this reason if Your Honor, please.I believe that the petitioner with his particular characteristics, his lack of training, some grave question as to what his mentality was, whether not even psychotic, no question about him being psychopathic, need of background, his youth, strangeness to the city, being incarcerated at the time that the so-called consent was given to him, I think that in this area that the -- and voluntariness within the contemplation of the federal rule that consents to search must be voluntary cannot be arrived at so that I have a two-pronged attack on the consent to search.","start":26.54,"stop":77.356,"duration":50.82},{"text":"One is that it was a fruit of illegal detention and I think that the McNabb (Inaudible) certainly or logically would apply to anything gained as a result of illegal detention.","start":77.356,"stop":89.999,"duration":12.64},{"text":"And then the other side of the coin that it was not voluntary in the -- according to the standard adopted by this jurisdiction.","start":89.999,"stop":98.499,"duration":8.5},{"text":"Inasmuch as that's so, I think that the evidence admitted depends -- the trial wasn't -- the defendant -- that the petitioner who should not have been admitted and that their introduction was error which should cause the case to be reversed.","start":98.499,"stop":109.9,"duration":11.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I just want to ask you one question before you take your seat, Mr. Bryant.","start":109.9,"stop":112.816,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":112.816,"stop":114.116,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the record give details, particulars, to substantiate your statement that the defendant here was at disadvantage, a person of limited capacity?","start":114.116,"stop":127.733,"duration":13.62}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, if Your Honor please.","start":127.733,"stop":128.312,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's in the record?","start":128.312,"stop":129.173,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"The record.","start":129.173,"stop":129.863,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then.","start":129.863,"stop":130.551,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"At the very outset, the testimony of the psychiatrist.","start":130.551,"stop":133.052,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":133.052,"stop":136.912,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barrett.","start":136.912,"stop":140.502,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":140.502,"stop":143.222,"duration":2.72},{"text":"I should like to address myself first to the McNabb question and reserving the other two questions for later consideration.","start":143.222,"stop":153.102,"duration":9.88},{"text":"It's noteworthy that in this case; petitioner makes no claim that his confession was a result of coercion, physical or psychological.","start":153.102,"stop":162.575,"duration":9.47},{"text":"The petitioner himself testified in this case that he had been treated kindly and made no complaint with respect to actual coercion.","start":162.575,"stop":173.815,"duration":11.24},{"text":"The petitioner's claim on the McNabb point is essentially that Rule 5 (a) must be interpreted as forbidding any delay in taking a person before the committing magistrate, other than that physically necessary for locating a magistrate and transporting the prisoner there.","start":173.815,"stop":190.62,"duration":16.81},{"text":"We then argued that under the McNabb rule, any confession obtained during a period of delay and beyond that must be excluded.","start":190.62,"stop":198.54,"duration":7.92},{"text":"Now, the Government concedes, of course, that the police could have found a committing magistrate and brought the petitioner before him within a relatively short time after his arrest at 2:30 on a Thursday afternoon.","start":198.54,"stop":210.751,"duration":12.21},{"text":"It is the Government's petition -- position, the Rule 5 (a) must be given a broader interpretation.","start":210.751,"stop":217.481,"duration":6.73},{"text":"That delay may be necessary within the meaning of the Rule beyond the time physically necessary to take an arrested person before a magistrate.","start":217.481,"stop":226.821,"duration":9.34},{"text":"That the delay in this case was necessary on a reasonable interpretation of the Rule and that hence from McNabb rule does not apply to exclude this confession.","start":226.821,"stop":236.923,"duration":10.1},{"text":"The facts in this case, we think, are an excellent example of the reason why a mechanical interpretation of Rule 5 (a) as applying only to the time actually necessary to find a magistrate to take a man before him, would be an undesirable interpretation.","start":236.923,"stop":256.057,"duration":19.13},{"text":"Consider what you have here.","start":256.057,"stop":258.346,"duration":2.29},{"text":"A rape was committed in the basement of an apartment house.","start":258.346,"stop":262.7,"duration":4.35},{"text":"The facts are that this basement may be reached by a set of wooden stairs or through a door, into a janitor's apartment.","start":262.7,"stop":271.253,"duration":8.55},{"text":"The courts investing the right of the victim, tells the police that after she came down to this basement to do her washing, she heard nobody come down these set of wooden stairs.","start":271.253,"stop":284.095,"duration":12.84},{"text":"That's conceded.","start":284.095,"stop":285.865,"duration":1.77},{"text":"And the petitioner himself conceded that he had been in the room shortly before the rape and to help the victim with a hose.","start":285.865,"stop":296.459,"duration":10.59},{"text":"The inference at this point was that -- probability was that the person who committed the crime came from the janitor's apartment.","start":296.459,"stop":304.641,"duration":8.18},{"text":"The description given by the victim would have fitted generally, apparently, the petitioner and his two nephews.","start":304.641,"stop":313.853,"duration":9.21},{"text":"A tall, Negro with bright eyes, with a white hat, was about as much as the victim was able to say at this stage of the game.","start":313.853,"stop":324.703,"duration":10.85},{"text":"So, hereafter, preliminary investigation, the police were faced with the fact that on the physical evidence there was a reasonable suspicion at least that one of these three people committed the rape.","start":324.703,"stop":337.098,"duration":12.4},{"text":"Further investigation apparently disclosed that the petitioner and one of his nephews had disappeared.","start":337.098,"stop":344.469,"duration":7.37},{"text":"The next morning, at some point, it's not clear from the record.","start":344.469,"stop":347.919,"duration":3.45},{"text":"The police picked up the two nephews, brought them into the police station and questioned them.","start":347.919,"stop":353.577,"duration":5.66},{"text":"That record doesn't disclose how long or under what circumstances with respect to the crime.","start":353.577,"stop":360.268,"duration":6.69},{"text":"They finally found the petitioner at 2:30 in the afternoon.","start":360.268,"stop":363.518,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind finishing what they did with the nephews?","start":363.518,"stop":366.238,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The nephews stayed and I'll deal with that.","start":366.238,"stop":369.105,"duration":2.87},{"text":"The nephews were at the police station when the petitioner was brought in.","start":369.105,"stop":373.475,"duration":4.37},{"text":"They brought the petitioner in and they questioned him.","start":373.475,"stop":377.225,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Now, several officers were apparently present during the questioning though the record doesn't tell us much about this.","start":377.225,"stop":384.762,"duration":7.54},{"text":"And, it's well to remember that this case was tried well over a year after the arrest.","start":384.762,"stop":389.457,"duration":4.69},{"text":"So that everybody's memories with respect to the details were undoubtedly fuzzy.","start":389.457,"stop":396.347,"duration":6.89},{"text":"He was questioned -- it's probable, though the record is not entirely clear that he was questioned in the presence of his two nephews.","start":396.347,"stop":403.837,"duration":7.49},{"text":"He said that they --","start":403.837,"stop":404.993,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They picked up without a warrant?","start":404.993,"stop":407.943,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Insofar as I know, the record doesn't disclose anything on that but I assume he was picked up without a warrant.","start":407.943,"stop":413.979,"duration":6.04},{"text":"Apparently he testified.","start":413.979,"stop":415.269,"duration":1.29},{"text":"The petitioner testified that his nephews and his brother were questioned -- were present when he was questioned at this initial period.","start":415.269,"stop":422.611,"duration":7.34},{"text":"Officer (Inaudible) testified that the nephews were present, part of the time.","start":422.611,"stop":426.181,"duration":3.57},{"text":"One of the nephews testified that he didn't think the petitioner was questioned in his presence.","start":426.181,"stop":430.411,"duration":4.23},{"text":"That's about the state of the record on that point.","start":430.411,"stop":434.331,"duration":3.92},{"text":"After a period of questioning which was --","start":434.331,"stop":436.696,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But would that help -- would that help any if other suspects were in at the questioning?","start":436.696,"stop":442.026,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there were other suspects, plus his brother who apparently was not a suspect --","start":442.026,"stop":445.596,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I thought --","start":445.596,"stop":445.856,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- within this case.","start":445.856,"stop":446.206,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I thought all of them, they picked up were suspects.","start":446.206,"stop":449.076,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's -- I'm not -- this record isn't clear but my assumption from the record is the brother who was an older man evidently were -- was never suspected here.","start":449.076,"stop":456.656,"duration":7.58},{"text":"It was the two nephews and that record only shows interrogation of the defendant and the two nephew -- the petitioner and the two nephews.","start":456.656,"stop":464.379,"duration":7.72},{"text":"Nothing would respect to his brother.","start":464.379,"stop":466.629,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They've been interrogating in the morning of the two nephews?","start":466.629,"stop":470.889,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The record just doesn't disclose.","start":470.889,"stop":473.369,"duration":2.48},{"text":"Part -- there's nothing in the printed record, the original record that's on file with the court shows that the other nephews were brought in at some point during the morning -- they testified that they were brought in to the police station during the morning.","start":473.369,"stop":485.304,"duration":11.93},{"text":"But that -- that we assume they were questioned.","start":485.304,"stop":489.214,"duration":3.91},{"text":"But the record isn't clear.","start":489.214,"stop":490.234,"duration":1.02},{"text":"This wasn't brought into focus in the trial.","start":490.234,"stop":493.604,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Now the petitioner was brought in and he was questioned, the officer said 15 to 30 minutes, he said 30 to 45 minutes.","start":493.604,"stop":500.615,"duration":7.01},{"text":"After this questioning he was taken, this had been -- taken place apparently in the Identification Bureau.","start":500.615,"stop":506.605,"duration":5.99},{"text":"He was then taken to the Sex Squad office where in the presence, he testified of his brother and his two nephews, the police asked them if the three of them would consent to take a lie detector test to determine apparently who was telling the truth.","start":506.605,"stop":522.044,"duration":15.44},{"text":"Petitioner in his testimony doesn't question the voluntariness of his consent to take a lie detector test.","start":522.044,"stop":529.475,"duration":7.43},{"text":"And the nephews testified that -- that they were asked.","start":529.475,"stop":533.915,"duration":4.44},{"text":"And they all agreed to take the lie detector test.","start":533.915,"stop":537.831,"duration":3.92},{"text":"Now, all of the delay after this time was consumed in waiting for the officer to arrive, who gave lie detector test and in giving the test first to the two nephews and finally to the petitioner.","start":537.831,"stop":554.751,"duration":16.92},{"text":"The brothers alone -- fuzziness on this issue, the -- the record seems to bear out statement that from about 4 o'clock in the afternoon until 8 o'clock when the petitioner was taken in for the lie detector test, he sat on a chair in the Sex Squad office with one or both of his nephews.","start":554.751,"stop":577.366,"duration":22.62},{"text":"It's not clear whether his brother was there all or part of the time.","start":577.366,"stop":580.642,"duration":3.28},{"text":"He was apparently there at the beginning of this period.","start":580.642,"stop":583.992,"duration":3.35},{"text":"They were given food and drink.","start":583.992,"stop":586.272,"duration":2.28},{"text":"They received no other guarding.","start":586.272,"stop":587.832,"duration":1.56},{"text":"And that was implied in sitting in the back of an office where police were coming and going.","start":587.832,"stop":593.402,"duration":5.57},{"text":"We don't contend, of course, they were free to leave.","start":593.402,"stop":595.462,"duration":2.06},{"text":"There's no question about that.","start":595.462,"stop":597.932,"duration":2.47},{"text":"And while there's a little conflict on this, most of the evidence suggests that they weren't questioned during this time.","start":597.932,"stop":604.892,"duration":6.96},{"text":"Petitioner himself said that he didn't remember any questioning during this period.","start":604.892,"stop":608.242,"duration":3.35},{"text":"They just sat in the office and waited.","start":608.242,"stop":612.602,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":612.602,"stop":613.932,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"From -- in -- in the petitioner's case from 4 until 8.","start":613.932,"stop":616.512,"duration":2.58},{"text":"At 6 o'clock they sent out apparently for a lie detector --","start":616.512,"stop":619.332,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When did --","start":619.332,"stop":620.252,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":620.252,"stop":620.852,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind Mr. , when did the lie detector machinery and its operator turn it up?","start":620.852,"stop":626.028,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He came about 6 o'clock.","start":626.028,"stop":627.808,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Six o'clock.","start":627.808,"stop":628.518,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The consent was somewhere around four they -- and then they sent out and then he came in.","start":628.518,"stop":632.478,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was he subjected to this -- was the defendant subjected at once to the machine or --?","start":632.478,"stop":637.698,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":637.698,"stop":638.118,"duration":0.42},{"text":"The -- the -- he came at six and he took first one of the nephews for an hour, approximately.","start":638.118,"stop":645.41,"duration":7.29},{"text":"Then the other nephew for an hour and he got the petitioner at 8 o'clock.","start":645.41,"stop":650.81,"duration":5.4},{"text":"The man who offered --","start":650.81,"stop":651.95,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Probably in the meantime about -- the -- the victim wasn't called in for identification (Inaudible)","start":651.95,"stop":658.5,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":658.5,"stop":659.571,"duration":1.07},{"text":"This --","start":659.571,"stop":660.061,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Anything in the record to suggest that the defendant was advised of his right to counsel or was -- anything on that point?","start":660.061,"stop":667.15,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The record shows that -- the only thing the record shows on this is that at the point later -- much later on at which he was given the lie detector, in which he was given the lie detector or under which he signed the -- was about to sign the written confession, you'll find it in the bottom of page 42 of the record.","start":667.15,"stop":689.629,"duration":22.48},{"text":"After he'd been confronted with the complaining witness after he'd made the oral admissions --","start":689.629,"stop":694.77,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) he confronted with this?","start":694.77,"stop":696.73,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was around -- late at night around 11 o'clock.","start":696.73,"stop":700.57,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before arraignment or after?","start":700.57,"stop":703.668,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It was before -- actual arraignment -- it was after the police made an attempt to get in touch with the commissioner.","start":703.668,"stop":709.848,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before arraignment?","start":709.848,"stop":710.858,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":710.858,"stop":711.614,"duration":0.76},{"text":"He was arraigned the next morning after all these happened, sometime during the morning.","start":711.614,"stop":715.324,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you one more question.","start":715.324,"stop":717.144,"duration":1.82},{"text":"Suppose he had declined to subject himself to the lie detector or suppose he had a lawyer and the lawyer said, \"Don't you submit to that,\" and he -- that would have been clearly within his rights wouldn't it?","start":717.144,"stop":729.604,"duration":12.46}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":729.604,"stop":732.174,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the lawyer had said, \"Don't you do it.","start":732.174,"stop":735.024,"duration":2.85},{"text":"The lie detector is not yet established as a wonderful scientific instrument.","start":735.024,"stop":738.505,"duration":3.48},{"text":"There are doubts and worries about the conditions under which it's given, et cetera.","start":738.505,"stop":742.015,"duration":3.51},{"text":"All the things that you and I know.\"","start":742.015,"stop":743.985,"duration":1.97},{"text":"That will be all right, wouldn't it?","start":743.985,"stop":745.885,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":745.885,"stop":747.835,"duration":1.95},{"text":"However, we don't know.","start":747.835,"stop":750.595,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know we don't know.","start":750.595,"stop":751.025,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":751.025,"stop":751.305,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But all I'm saying is that all that period was utilized and -- and his subjection to this -- to this prosecutorial -- I'm not questioning any -- prior to this prosecutorial intention that about having any counsel on his side or any advice or any knowledge of what his rights were.","start":751.305,"stop":771.487,"duration":20.18}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I should add that there's nothing in the record that suggests that had he wanted counsel, he could not have had it.","start":771.487,"stop":778.117,"duration":6.63},{"text":"He wasn't isolated from family and friends at least in the sense of being secreted in the back room.","start":778.117,"stop":783.267,"duration":5.15},{"text":"He was held in an office, his brother was evidently in and out.","start":783.267,"stop":788.087,"duration":4.82},{"text":"And the -- the situation is -- is different but not, I suggest, perhaps materially, different than if he'd been asked the question in his home when you come down to the police station and take the lie detector test.","start":788.087,"stop":800.917,"duration":12.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want to delay your conclusion.","start":800.917,"stop":803.991,"duration":3.07},{"text":"You can draw from it.","start":803.991,"stop":805.111,"duration":1.12},{"text":"But will dispose in a word of the character of this defendant.","start":805.111,"stop":809.691,"duration":4.58},{"text":"Do you agree or disagree with Mr. -- that the general impression that Mr. Bryant's statements left on with me especially the kind of a person you were dealing with.","start":809.691,"stop":819.513,"duration":9.82}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the evidence is somewhat more conflicting on this issue than Mr. Bryant suggested.","start":819.513,"stop":825.413,"duration":5.9},{"text":"Actually one psychiatrist whose testimony or that appears here in -- in the record that's before you on page -- page 4, a Dr. (Inaudible) saw that petitioner for an hour from the jail, a few days after the event.","start":825.413,"stop":849.856,"duration":24.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 4 of what?","start":849.856,"stop":851.536,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the transcript, that's before here.","start":851.536,"stop":854.566,"duration":3.03},{"text":"It's a letter report --","start":854.566,"stop":855.836,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, a letter.","start":855.836,"stop":856.616,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- appears at the bottom.","start":856.616,"stop":857.976,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Whose -- whose witness -- whose psychiatrist was he?","start":857.976,"stop":860.566,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Appointed by the court.","start":860.566,"stop":861.666,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Appointed by the court?","start":861.666,"stop":862.266,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"At this point, appointed three psychiatrists to determine the issue of sanity.","start":862.266,"stop":866.326,"duration":4.06},{"text":"The three came in with or that I guess that was two.","start":866.326,"stop":871.306,"duration":4.98},{"text":"The two came in with this -- agreed that he was mentally ill at the time.","start":871.306,"stop":876.297,"duration":4.99},{"text":"Now, this particular psychiatrist also said the patient appeared to be dull and apathetic and mildly confused.","start":876.297,"stop":883.727,"duration":7.43},{"text":"No former psychological test were given but the estimate of his intelligence, is that of a moron.","start":883.727,"stop":888.89,"duration":5.16},{"text":"Now, he was sent to St.Elizabeth and after 90 days was sent back.","start":888.89,"stop":893.302,"duration":4.41},{"text":"The three doctors from St.Elizabeth testified that he wasn't insane.","start":893.302,"stop":897.462,"duration":4.16},{"text":"That he hadn't been at the time he came or they filed a report testified that he hasn't been insane at the time he came to them and that on their -- on their investigation he wasn't.","start":897.462,"stop":907.785,"duration":10.32},{"text":"Now, later on, now it is not in this transcript.","start":907.785,"stop":910.395,"duration":2.61},{"text":"It's in the original transcript.","start":910.395,"stop":911.795,"duration":1.4},{"text":"Dr. (Inaudible) testified in this case.","start":911.795,"stop":915.682,"duration":3.89},{"text":"It appears, beginning at page 365 of the type-written transcript.","start":915.682,"stop":921.652,"duration":5.97},{"text":"In -- in which again he repeated his assertion that the petitioner was a high grade moron.","start":921.652,"stop":925.996,"duration":4.34},{"text":"But again this testimony was based on his hour of examination of a year and two months, previously.","start":925.996,"stop":931.546,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean his trial was before the Government (Inaudible) wasn't it?","start":931.546,"stop":935.655,"duration":4.11},{"text":"When was that?","start":935.655,"stop":935.665,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so, I'm not sure.","start":935.665,"stop":937.835,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure either.","start":937.835,"stop":938.635,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":938.635,"stop":939.935,"duration":1.3},{"text":"But at any rate, none of the other people who testified said anything directly about -- none of the other doctors got to the issue of the petitioner's intelligence.","start":939.935,"stop":949.517,"duration":9.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I didn't mean so much his actual mental state.","start":949.517,"stop":951.977,"duration":2.46},{"text":"But as the record disclose (Inaudible)","start":951.977,"stop":954.176,"duration":2.2},{"text":"The record discloses education is what kind of stability?","start":954.176,"stop":958.166,"duration":3.99},{"text":"I don't mean --","start":958.166,"stop":958.476,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":958.476,"stop":958.556,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- psychological.","start":958.556,"stop":959.286,"duration":0.73},{"text":"Was he pending on that in the record?","start":959.286,"stop":961.286,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Very little.","start":961.286,"stop":961.746,"duration":0.46},{"text":"He stated to one of the (Voice Overlap) --","start":961.746,"stop":963.186,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How old is he?","start":963.186,"stop":964.486,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He was 19 at this time.","start":964.486,"stop":965.456,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"19?","start":965.456,"stop":966.386,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He stated to one of the doctors that -- who -- according to the doctor that he was, \"How far did you go school in \"Eight grade?","start":966.386,"stop":973.646,"duration":7.26},{"text":"\"How did you do?\"","start":973.646,"stop":974.016,"duration":0.37},{"text":"\"I did good.\"","start":974.016,"stop":975.246,"duration":1.23},{"text":"He stated on his oral examination that he went to the seventh grade in school.","start":975.246,"stop":981.056,"duration":5.81},{"text":"And that's about all the --","start":981.056,"stop":982.696,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he have a permanent occupation?","start":982.696,"stop":984.348,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Did anything appear on that?","start":984.348,"stop":986.928,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's nothing in the printed record here as I remember from looking over the written transcript.","start":986.928,"stop":992.233,"duration":5.3},{"text":"He -- he had come up to the -- from -- he had come here not -- two or three months before the event from Greenville, South Carolina for six or seven weeks.","start":992.233,"stop":1005.773,"duration":13.54},{"text":"And as I remember in the transcript it shows that he'd been taken some trips in the moving van and in fact the day that -- when he'd gone out somewhere in Maryland to look for a job and -- but no permanent fixed occupation.","start":1005.773,"stop":1017.971,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What does a part of the record includes as to the (Inaudible)","start":1017.971,"stop":1023.511,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the -- that's the theory on which it was constructed.","start":1023.511,"stop":1025.921,"duration":2.41},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1025.921,"stop":1026.231,"duration":0.31},{"text":"Though there are some other portions that might be.","start":1026.231,"stop":1029.911,"duration":3.68},{"text":"Though -- though most of them are here as a printed record.","start":1029.911,"stop":1033.05,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Were you suggesting, Mr. Barrett, that the original record would indicate a difference in Dr.(Inaudible) testimony over the findings?","start":1033.05,"stop":1040.306,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No his testimony -- his testimony was the same.","start":1040.306,"stop":1043.246,"duration":2.94},{"text":"All I was suggesting is that -- that he stood along and assessing the man as a moron.","start":1043.246,"stop":1049.656,"duration":6.41},{"text":"That everybody else that had anything to do with him on this day testified that he was bright and alert, cooperative.","start":1049.656,"stop":1056.926,"duration":7.27},{"text":"His own testimony as your read it here in the record suggests a relatively high degree of ability to verbalize concepts and to respond to questions.","start":1056.926,"stop":1067.334,"duration":10.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you have heard this point whether the total time which was -- interrogation of this man proved the interrogation (Inaudible)","start":1067.334,"stop":1077.354,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, at -- at 2:30 or 3 o'clock he was somewhere between 15 and 45 minutes, the longest estimate is 45.","start":1077.354,"stop":1085.6,"duration":8.25},{"text":"The petitioner says 30 to 45 and then it was an hour and a half that he was with Officer McCarthy in the room with the polygraph at which apparently about 20 to 25 minutes was consumed with asking questions while he was hooked up to the machine.","start":1085.6,"stop":1101.835,"duration":16.24},{"text":"He was asked the questions ahead of this and after.","start":1101.835,"stop":1105.751,"duration":3.92},{"text":"Then after that hour and a half when he had confessed to Officer McCarthy, then other officers were brought in and he repeated his confession to them.","start":1105.751,"stop":1114.011,"duration":8.26},{"text":"Now, the record doesn't disclose quite how long that took, apparently 10 or 15 minutes.","start":1114.011,"stop":1118.757,"duration":4.75},{"text":"And when he repeated the -- the confession to them, and then later on he -- he repeated it to the complaining witness and ultimately he dictated to a type-writer, a written and signed confession here.","start":1118.757,"stop":1132.053,"duration":13.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Overall who (Inaudible) two and a half to three hours.","start":1132.053,"stop":1138.693,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1138.693,"stop":1140.433,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was --","start":1140.433,"stop":1140.733,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"With this intervening period of time.","start":1140.733,"stop":1142.413,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the defense, Mr. Barrett?","start":1142.413,"stop":1145.233,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That the petitioner --","start":1145.233,"stop":1146.003,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I infer from what you said that he took the stand.","start":1146.003,"stop":1148.293,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the petitioner's defense was that he didn't remember anything that happened after 6:30 in the evening.","start":1148.293,"stop":1154.683,"duration":6.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't mean on this issue.","start":1154.683,"stop":1156.193,"duration":1.51},{"text":"I mean the defense on the merits?","start":1156.193,"stop":1157.853,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- he denied doing it, and he testified that he didn't remember all his confession business He didn't remember anything that happened after 6:30.","start":1157.853,"stop":1169.431,"duration":11.58},{"text":"And I don't know that there was much more than that.","start":1169.431,"stop":1174.871,"duration":5.44},{"text":"The flat denial, the --","start":1174.871,"stop":1176.761,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And on the identification -- identification by the victim.","start":1176.761,"stop":1181.101,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not clear.","start":1181.101,"stop":1182.641,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not clear?","start":1182.641,"stop":1183.731,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As I read the -- the record.","start":1183.731,"stop":1185.491,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1185.491,"stop":1189.508,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"She -- she said, at least in the part of the record that's here.","start":1189.508,"stop":1193.198,"duration":3.69},{"text":"She -- she testified that at the time it happened, she wouldn't have identified the defendant as being the same person that had been in the room previously.","start":1193.198,"stop":1204.718,"duration":11.52},{"text":"That all she can say was that he fit the same general description.","start":1204.718,"stop":1208.889,"duration":4.17},{"text":"Now --","start":1208.889,"stop":1209.689,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I asked that question because some of the cases -- indeed this Court points out -- has pointed out that (Inaudible) towards alleged errors of this one finding, may be influenced by the -- by the certainty of a -- the convincingness of proof.","start":1209.689,"stop":1225.119,"duration":15.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The --","start":1225.119,"stop":1225.539,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming there's enough to go the jury anyhow.","start":1225.539,"stop":1227.135,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1227.135,"stop":1228.065,"duration":0.93},{"text":"The -- the way the -- the way that confession went here, the -- the defendant avoided any question about it simply by saying he thought he'd been drugged when they gave him food and drink.","start":1228.065,"stop":1241.827,"duration":13.76},{"text":"He didn't remember anything after 6:30 until he woke up in the jail the next morning.","start":1241.827,"stop":1246.001,"duration":4.17},{"text":"And therefore, he wouldn't affirm or deny what had happened in this intervening period.","start":1246.001,"stop":1250.131,"duration":4.13},{"text":"He said it looked like his signature but he couldn't remember signing it with someone.","start":1250.131,"stop":1253.595,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- there are two different questions.","start":1253.595,"stop":1256.845,"duration":3.25},{"text":"What I was just referring to is the -- the certainly or the confidence in which one can say, guilt was established by the proof apart form the confession.","start":1256.845,"stop":1269.195,"duration":12.35},{"text":"Not, the confidence one can have, the confession is valid.","start":1269.195,"stop":1273.518,"duration":4.32},{"text":"I'm saying that the case is -- I think has indicated pretty clearly that makes a difference how you feel about diversity.","start":1273.518,"stop":1281.205,"duration":7.69},{"text":"How solid the proof is on -- on controverting -- controvertible the proof is, on the merits apart from the contested (Voice Overlap) --","start":1281.205,"stop":1288.025,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose you know what you have to say instead of we'll say, case of circumstantial evidence here, apart from the confession and especially if you say apart from the clothes which had seminal stains and so on which were introduced.","start":1288.025,"stop":1300.471,"duration":12.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there not -- suppose you took -- suppose you took out of the case the confession that he gave and the evidence that was obtained by the search of the house that you say was a part and parcel of the same conversation while he was detained.","start":1300.471,"stop":1315.871,"duration":15.4},{"text":"What would be left in the case?","start":1315.871,"stop":1319.025,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I Suppose what would be left, my familiarity with the record here is not all that it might be that entire record, but I assume what would be left was the fact that he had been in the room with the victim shortly before he conceded that and seen her there.","start":1319.025,"stop":1335.255,"duration":16.23},{"text":"That he testified that he was the only person in the adjoining apartment.","start":1335.255,"stop":1342.613,"duration":7.36},{"text":"His brother or his nephews testified that they weren't there at the crucial time.","start":1342.613,"stop":1348.846,"duration":6.23},{"text":"The victim testified that she heard nobody come down the wooden steps from which you could infer that person came in from the apartment.","start":1348.846,"stop":1356.923,"duration":8.08},{"text":"He met the general description of the person who committed the rape.","start":1356.923,"stop":1362.592,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How old are these nephews, Mr. Barrett?","start":1362.592,"stop":1364.762,"duration":2.17},{"text":"Does that appear --","start":1364.762,"stop":1366.252,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure.","start":1366.252,"stop":1366.872,"duration":0.62},{"text":"I don't think it shows from the record.","start":1366.872,"stop":1368.402,"duration":1.53},{"text":"They were evidently adults.","start":1368.402,"stop":1372.392,"duration":3.99},{"text":"Or I don't -- I don't know the answer to that.","start":1372.392,"stop":1376.142,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Well, our -- our contention on the McNabb point here then is that under these circumstances, a serious crime of violence had been committed.","start":1376.142,"stop":1386.712,"duration":10.57},{"text":"The police had reasonable grounds for suspecting one or three persons, either the nephews or the petitioner had committed this crime.","start":1386.712,"stop":1398.907,"duration":12.19},{"text":"The police, upon arresting the petitioner could not very well have taken him immediately before a magistrate and singled him out to file a complaint that he was the person who had done it.","start":1398.907,"stop":1412.787,"duration":13.88},{"text":"They couldn't have done it with anyone of the three at the point at which they brought him in.","start":1412.787,"stop":1418.459,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I understand Mr. Bryant to say they were also bringing in other people for this same crime?","start":1418.459,"stop":1423.909,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That apparently the only people (Inaudible) the record, the only people that were suspected were the -- were the petitioner and his two nephews.","start":1423.909,"stop":1430.939,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I see.","start":1430.939,"stop":1431.749,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And they were all there.","start":1431.749,"stop":1433.216,"duration":1.47},{"text":"They were all three interrogated.","start":1433.216,"stop":1435.056,"duration":1.84},{"text":"They all consented to the lie detector test.","start":1435.056,"stop":1437.086,"duration":2.03},{"text":"They all took --","start":1437.086,"stop":1437.996,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you --","start":1437.996,"stop":1438.306,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the lie detector test.","start":1438.306,"stop":1439.206,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- did you say a little while ago that the nephews or one of them wasn't in the rule of the three?","start":1439.206,"stop":1445.096,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- apparently they were --","start":1445.096,"stop":1446.566,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How could they have been then suspected if -- if --","start":1446.566,"stop":1448.706,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I --","start":1448.706,"stop":1448.936,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it had to be one of the three in that room?","start":1448.936,"stop":1451.128,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I don't mean in that room.","start":1451.128,"stop":1452.468,"duration":1.34},{"text":"I mean in the -- in the --","start":1452.468,"stop":1454.048,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Detention room.","start":1454.048,"stop":1454.058,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- police station, in the detention room.","start":1454.058,"stop":1455.668,"duration":1.61},{"text":"They were in and out but --","start":1455.668,"stop":1458.018,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It conceded the three people or wasn't one of the three, the janitor?","start":1458.018,"stop":1462.955,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that the -- the father of the nephews, the brother of the petitioner was the janitor.","start":1462.955,"stop":1467.965,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh.","start":1467.965,"stop":1468.035,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's why he lived there.","start":1468.035,"stop":1470.205,"duration":2.17},{"text":"And the petitioner --","start":1470.205,"stop":1470.805,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that the three -- so that the potential, the possible defendant, possible -- guilty people was the janitor, this -- his brother and a nephew?","start":1470.805,"stop":1483.175,"duration":12.37}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm not sure.","start":1483.175,"stop":1484.355,"duration":1.18},{"text":"The record doesn't answer this, but I get the impression that the brother wasn't suspected.","start":1484.355,"stop":1488.225,"duration":3.87},{"text":"Maybe he didn't --","start":1488.225,"stop":1488.395,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't suspected?","start":1488.395,"stop":1489.295,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe he didn't -- maybe he didn't met -- meet the general physical description.","start":1489.295,"stop":1491.605,"duration":2.31},{"text":"That I don't know.","start":1491.605,"stop":1492.595,"duration":0.99},{"text":"It was the two nephews and his two sons, in other words and the defendant, petitioner here who were the suspects.","start":1492.595,"stop":1502.996,"duration":10.4},{"text":"Now, under these circumstances, to say to the police that you have to either not take these people in and question them or you have to pick one out and taking, and file a charge, a complaint against them before a Commissioner.","start":1502.996,"stop":1524.145,"duration":21.15},{"text":"They weren't in the position to do this.","start":1524.145,"stop":1525.865,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Now, this is not like Upshaw.","start":1525.865,"stop":1529.015,"duration":3.15},{"text":"In the Upshaw case, you had a different situation.","start":1529.015,"stop":1531.466,"duration":2.45},{"text":"You had the police suspecting an individual, had the policeman of the court know or was testifying that the reason they held this individual is to get a confession from him.","start":1531.466,"stop":1545.136,"duration":13.67},{"text":"Here you have a different situation.","start":1545.136,"stop":1547.236,"duration":2.1},{"text":"You have three logical suspects.","start":1547.236,"stop":1549.495,"duration":2.26},{"text":"The reason the police did what they did here was to try to eliminate.","start":1549.495,"stop":1555.655,"duration":6.16},{"text":"There, about the only investigative technique left to the police in this case at this time was to question the suspects.","start":1555.655,"stop":1563.129,"duration":7.47},{"text":"They weren't going to get physical evidence that would pick anybody out.","start":1563.129,"stop":1567.269,"duration":4.14},{"text":"They were going to be no eyewitnesses.","start":1567.269,"stop":1569.979,"duration":2.71},{"text":"And so they were questioning these three people who logically might have committed the crime under these circumstances.","start":1569.979,"stop":1577.195,"duration":7.22},{"text":"I assume that the petitioner never confessed.","start":1577.195,"stop":1580.335,"duration":3.14},{"text":"That -- that on -- as a result of the questioning the police have then let loose the two nephews and charged him with the crime.","start":1580.335,"stop":1588.05,"duration":7.71},{"text":"That there wouldn't be as much feeling about illegality as there is here because he ultimately did -- he ultimately did confess.","start":1588.05,"stop":1599.667,"duration":11.62},{"text":"There are lots of other situations which are just similar to this one.","start":1599.667,"stop":1604.747,"duration":5.08},{"text":"The police for example, a man is shot in the street.","start":1604.747,"stop":1608.547,"duration":3.8},{"text":"Officers rushing to the scene may see two or three people running away.","start":1608.547,"stop":1613.643,"duration":5.1},{"text":"Maybe somebody in the crowd says, \"He shot him, he shot him.\"","start":1613.643,"stop":1617.793,"duration":4.15},{"text":"Under the circumstances they have to make an arrest.","start":1617.793,"stop":1621.363,"duration":3.57},{"text":"And they have to make some inquiry before they take the step of filing a formal charge against one of these individuals with the crime.","start":1621.363,"stop":1634.178,"duration":12.82},{"text":"It seems to be generally conceded by most of the authorities that -- that there is a necessity for some amount of investigation in this kind of a situation.","start":1634.178,"stop":1647.201,"duration":13.02},{"text":"Now, there may be serious questions as to how best it should be done.","start":1647.201,"stop":1651.991,"duration":4.79},{"text":"The Government, of course, is sympathetic with the -- with the underlying purpose of the McNabb rule.","start":1651.991,"stop":1658.167,"duration":6.18},{"text":"We recognize the evils of secret interrogation, the evils of the -- of the third degree.","start":1658.167,"stop":1665.757,"duration":7.59},{"text":"But we suggest however, to apply the McNabb rule, purely mechanically, is only a question of time.","start":1665.757,"stop":1673.094,"duration":7.34},{"text":"It goes too far and rules out, confessions that are -- or rules out, it's not just that it rules out confessions but brand this illegal, perfectly reasonable police practices which have nothing to do with beating up the man in the back room.","start":1673.094,"stop":1689.599,"duration":16.5},{"text":"This case is -- is a good example.","start":1689.599,"stop":1692.309,"duration":2.71},{"text":"It could not be said that the petitioner here was held incommunicado.","start":1692.309,"stop":1696.387,"duration":4.08},{"text":"That he was secreted in the back room.","start":1696.387,"stop":1698.877,"duration":2.49},{"text":"He was held out in the -- with his nephews, apparently with his brother in the offices of the police.","start":1698.877,"stop":1705.707,"duration":6.83},{"text":"The only time in which he could be said to have been taken off into the back room is the hour and a half that he spent with the polygraph operator and where the -- he was questioned in this -- this small room.","start":1705.707,"stop":1719.417,"duration":13.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barrett, as you well know, McNabb isn't merely concerned, wasn't concern merely with a fellow being beaten up in the back room.","start":1719.417,"stop":1728.743,"duration":9.33},{"text":"It was concerned primarily that occasion be made out against the defendant to his -- to himself.","start":1728.743,"stop":1735.596,"duration":6.85},{"text":"Now, of course, if you got beating up from the back room that night, everybody is used to that.","start":1735.596,"stop":1742.016,"duration":6.42},{"text":"But --","start":1742.016,"stop":1743.066,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, the Government are -- The Government's position here is that it would certainly be a -- a drastic change in law enforcement practices and we suggest it's nothing --","start":1743.066,"stop":1756.113,"duration":13.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The McNabb rule was intended very considerably to change conventional methods of law enforcement.","start":1756.113,"stop":1762.975,"duration":6.86},{"text":"That's the point of the rule.","start":1762.975,"stop":1766.285,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's nothing in what was said or decided in McNabb or Upshaw which carries it as far as the contention made in this case.","start":1766.285,"stop":1774.295,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That maybe.","start":1774.295,"stop":1776.035,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":1776.035,"stop":1776.285,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it wasn't merely a rule designed to prevent physical violence as a mode of extorting confession.","start":1776.285,"stop":1785.845,"duration":9.56},{"text":"That was precisely indicated that that was not the reason for it or even for it and it didn't want to create circumstances as I indicated in which you get stuff out of the defendant and have -- instead of having the Government, the prosecutor generally go about the business in establishing through resourceful energy and imagination and enterprise, a case other than out of the mouth of the defendant.","start":1785.845,"stop":1808.528,"duration":22.68}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This case I think, Your Honor, is a good example of the situation in which if you don't permit police interrogation of the suspects, you don't convict people.","start":1808.528,"stop":1820.768,"duration":12.24},{"text":"You get often, these cases where the resources of the physical evidence of eye witnesses are exhausted and -- and what you have left is the need for some names under which the police can interrogate these people.","start":1820.768,"stop":1838.93,"duration":18.16},{"text":"They -- they had to talk to these three people in the interest of the society.","start":1838.93,"stop":1841.96,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I saw it here.","start":1841.96,"stop":1843.11,"duration":1.15},{"text":"The fellow had a lawyer who told him, you don't open your mouth.","start":1843.11,"stop":1846.65,"duration":3.54},{"text":"You -- the police wouldn't have (Inaudible) up their head and said, \"We can file about this case.\"","start":1846.65,"stop":1850.82,"duration":4.17},{"text":"Wouldn't they?","start":1850.82,"stop":1851.906,"duration":1.09},{"text":"I shouldn't imagine that responsible police would do that.","start":1851.906,"stop":1854.426,"duration":2.52},{"text":"They will -- if he can't get it out of his own mouth, therefore we stop doing anything.","start":1854.426,"stop":1858.656,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But presumably if -- if only his lawyer told him that, the police would still have the evidence that they received from the statements of the people who were not guilty, in this case, the two nephews.","start":1858.656,"stop":1872.83,"duration":14.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if the police went on -- at least prove the nephews didn't do it.","start":1872.83,"stop":1876.36,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But it would tend to prove under the circumstances of this case that the Commissioner did.","start":1876.36,"stop":1880.09,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that wouldn't be -- you could put that in a proof in the trial.","start":1880.09,"stop":1883.21,"duration":3.12},{"text":"At least three fellows were in the room, the two others have been established and are innocent ergo, this fellow, you may find guilty.","start":1883.21,"stop":1889.931,"duration":6.72},{"text":"You don't suggest that freely, do you?","start":1889.931,"stop":1892.571,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but -- but their stories about where they were which could be checked about where they saw the petitioner and so on are all related to the -- to the issue of -- of guilt.","start":1892.571,"stop":1902.317,"duration":9.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barrett, if he had not gone on the lie detector, how long would you say that they could have kept him in this same condition and still have the Government here in court saying that it referred to be proper?","start":1902.317,"stop":1919.168,"duration":16.85}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I don't know how you answer -- answer the -- the how long.","start":1919.168,"stop":1923.238,"duration":4.07},{"text":"I would assume that what would be proper here would be a reasonable amount of time which might be 30 minutes or two hours, I suppose, depending on the circumstances and how complicated the situation was, for getting the stories of the people.","start":1923.238,"stop":1939.374,"duration":16.14},{"text":"Now, the police were in the position of having gotten each -- each man's story.","start":1939.374,"stop":1944.924,"duration":5.55},{"text":"And it was at that point that the suggestion was made that, will you be willing to take the lie detector test?","start":1944.924,"stop":1951.742,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Presumably, the two that were innocent felt they had nothing to lose by taking the lie detector test and I suppose perhaps the force of circumstances, the guilty man maybe was forced under the circumstances to consent too, because he was (Voice Overlap) --","start":1951.742,"stop":1969.15,"duration":17.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I thought the record showed that he was eager and some -- the Government --","start":1969.15,"stop":1971.77,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1971.77,"stop":1971.96,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- relies on --","start":1971.96,"stop":1972.97,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1972.97,"stop":1973.19,"duration":0.22},{"text":"He -- he said --","start":1973.19,"stop":1973.673,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the Government (Inaudible) said he was eager for this.","start":1973.673,"stop":1976.113,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1976.113,"stop":1978.313,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Well, so that we --","start":1978.313,"stop":1980.893,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, that responsiveness to a request to take a lie detector proved innocence (Inaudible)","start":1980.893,"stop":1986.073,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I didn't say that the response proved it.","start":1986.073,"stop":1987.993,"duration":1.92},{"text":"I merely said that -- that after the initial brief period of questioning, the -- the only thing that went on beyond this came because everybody said, \"We want to prove we're innocent.","start":1987.993,"stop":2001.774,"duration":13.78},{"text":"We'd like to take the lie detector test.\"","start":2001.774,"stop":2004.174,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Beyond this, the police -- the holding was all for that purpose.","start":2004.174,"stop":2007.124,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So, what do you with the language of the statute that says when he's arrested he shall be taken without unnecessary delay to -- to a magistrate?","start":2007.124,"stop":2016.404,"duration":9.28},{"text":"What do you do with that language?","start":2016.404,"stop":2018.384,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we say that -- that the delay here was necessary.","start":2018.384,"stop":2021.784,"duration":3.4},{"text":"That it depends on how you construe, of course, the word \"necessary.\"","start":2021.784,"stop":2024.964,"duration":3.18},{"text":"The earlier --","start":2024.964,"stop":2025.204,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"By necessary -- by necessary, unnecessary delay, you mean that they can take him and hold him as long as they are investigating him and need to do so in order to determine whether he committed this crime or not, is that right?","start":2025.204,"stop":2042.29,"duration":17.09}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, we don't take the position that far.","start":2042.29,"stop":2045.128,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2045.128,"stop":2045.438,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We take the position that you have to look at the facts of each case to determine whether the delay in this particular case was necessary or unnecessary within the meaning of the rule.","start":2045.438,"stop":2059.789,"duration":14.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the Commissioner was right there at the time in building or in -- in the room, would you have been justified in not arraigning him or not to -- not to bring him (Inaudible)--","start":2059.789,"stop":2072.215,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government's position is that --","start":2072.215,"stop":2073.255,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- until such time as you -- you might have completed the investigation?","start":2073.255,"stop":2078.554,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government's position is that in - on the fact of this case --","start":2078.554,"stop":2081.882,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2081.882,"stop":2082.112,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- they would have had no duty to take him to the Commissioner even though he's been in the room.","start":2082.112,"stop":2086.552,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any statute which authorizes you have at least to summon a man to give evidence before them as -- the way this man gave evidence?","start":2086.552,"stop":2097.023,"duration":10.47},{"text":"Is there any statute which specifically authorizes that?","start":2097.023,"stop":2101.033,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not as far I know, Your Honor.","start":2101.033,"stop":2104.123,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no contention that this man was not arrested is there?","start":2104.123,"stop":2108.329,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2108.329,"stop":2108.549,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2108.549,"stop":2110.119,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually the problem here it seems to me stems from the fact that we haven't had an exercise of either statutory or rule making power to spell out precisely what it is the police ought to be able to do.","start":2110.119,"stop":2122.939,"duration":12.82},{"text":"Many authorities have contended over the years that there should be some regularized procedure for questioning suspects.","start":2122.939,"stop":2130.898,"duration":7.96},{"text":"That maybe it should be done, some suggestions have been made that it should be done by the Commissioner.","start":2130.898,"stop":2136.058,"duration":5.16},{"text":"Other suggestions, the Uniform Arrest Act, for example, suggested that the police should -- that the police should be able to take the man before the Commissioner and the Commissioner should have discretion to release him to the custody of the police for up to 48 hours for reasonable investigation before the police would have the necessity to file a -- a complaint.","start":2136.058,"stop":2156.117,"duration":20.06},{"text":"We haven't had either to rule making or to the legislature a careful spelling out of what ought to be done.","start":2156.117,"stop":2166.259,"duration":10.14},{"text":"Now -- now we suggest that the -- that the position of society is not just the police who're suspecting here.","start":2166.259,"stop":2174.829,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Obviously the interests in society are that we ought to apprehend people who commit rape, other serious crimes.","start":2174.829,"stop":2181.749,"duration":6.92},{"text":"Obviously the privacy of the victim here was very severely debated and perhaps there was a risk of the privacy of other women, would -- would be invaded.","start":2181.749,"stop":2192.656,"duration":10.91},{"text":"And that we have to balance in all of these cases the public interest in reducing private, illegal invasion to privacy among the public.","start":2192.656,"stop":2203.246,"duration":10.59},{"text":"Now, I recognize that public officers are obviously held to a higher standard, but we suggest that what was done here doesn't offend the moral sense and that it was certainly not clear to -- to the police here, for example, that what they were doing was a violation of law.","start":2203.246,"stop":2219.917,"duration":16.67},{"text":"As we point in our brief, almost without exception, the Courts of Appeals since McNabb and Upshaw have recognized in the cases the necessity for some detention other than that absolutely necessary to take the man before a magistrate.","start":2219.917,"stop":2238.297,"duration":18.38},{"text":"And there's a whole string of cases in this circuit and other circuits where the police have -- where the courts have not applied the McNabb rule in that literal mechanical sense that -- that the only thing is relevant.","start":2238.297,"stop":2252.388,"duration":14.09},{"text":"Such an application has certain curious circumstances, too, unrelated to the policy.","start":2252.388,"stop":2258.698,"duration":6.31},{"text":"If you couldn't find a magistrate the 24 hours, presumably then the police could question a man for 24 hours as long they didn't interfere with the voluntary rule.","start":2258.698,"stop":2269.108,"duration":10.41},{"text":"But in another case where you could find one in five minutes, you couldn't question him at all.","start":2269.108,"stop":2274.702,"duration":5.59},{"text":"And this doesn't seem to be the -- the correct solution to -- to the problem that's involved here.","start":2274.702,"stop":2283.272,"duration":8.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Barrett, is there any background to the phraseology of this rule to indicate that unnecessary delay contemplated the circumstances under which the delay was incident to an investigation after an arrest?","start":2283.272,"stop":2302.337,"duration":19.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, really all we know, I suppose is that the previous statutes that you set out in a footnote on page 22 of the Government's brief talked in terms of taking him forthwith before some judicial officer or the person arrested shall be immediately taken before a committing officer.","start":2302.337,"stop":2321.714,"duration":19.38},{"text":"Now, the -- the other people have out that the legislative history here originally was more in terms of cutting down on the expense money that the commission -- that the police got by taking them long distance is to arraignment rather than in the problem we're dealing with here but that's beside the point.","start":2321.714,"stop":2340.249,"duration":18.53},{"text":"When the Rule 5 (a) was promulgated, it didn't use forthwith It didn't use immediately.","start":2340.249,"stop":2346.539,"duration":6.29},{"text":"It used unnecessary delay.","start":2346.539,"stop":2348.469,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well just looking at it, on the face of the rule, would not unnecessary delay appeal reasonably as meaning only that the police upon an arrest to then use due diligence in locating a committing magistrate and nothing else?","start":2348.469,"stop":2370.728,"duration":22.26},{"text":"The circumstance you mentioned, there might be a magistrate some hundreds of miles distance, the nearest one, does this contemplate though, every effort should be made upon arrest immediately to get him to a committing magistrate?","start":2370.728,"stop":2385.168,"duration":14.44}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They --","start":2385.168,"stop":2385.238,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On the face of it","start":2385.238,"stop":2386.168,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2386.168,"stop":2386.478,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's all we have to go by.","start":2386.478,"stop":2387.848,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, well, we -- we -- the Government's position is that unnecessary must be interpreted to mean something other than purely this physical time mechanical rule how long does it take to (Voice Overlap)","start":2387.848,"stop":2402.266,"duration":14.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm just among them.","start":2402.266,"stop":2403.476,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Why do say that?","start":2403.476,"stop":2405.476,"duration":2},{"text":"Well, is it directing in the rule would suggest that?","start":2405.476,"stop":2409.426,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all we have is the word.","start":2409.426,"stop":2410.939,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":2410.939,"stop":2411.339,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All we have is the word unnecessary.","start":2411.339,"stop":2413.789,"duration":2.45},{"text":"And -- and we can contend we -- our contention --","start":2413.789,"stop":2415.839,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But we have a little more than that.","start":2415.839,"stop":2417.379,"duration":1.54},{"text":"We had great conflict within the advisory committee whether McNabb should be made into a rule.","start":2417.379,"stop":2423.392,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But that didn't deal with the problem we're faced with here.","start":2423.392,"stop":2427.122,"duration":3.73},{"text":"That is, the proposal there was to -- to say if you don't take the man within this period, whatever it is, you have to exclude the confession.","start":2427.122,"stop":2435.546,"duration":8.42},{"text":"And that ultimately didn't get in.","start":2435.546,"stop":2437.316,"duration":1.77},{"text":"But that didn't deal with the question of what's meant by unnecessary.","start":2437.316,"stop":2440.934,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that doesn't -- couldn't give a definition.","start":2440.934,"stop":2443.064,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't.","start":2443.064,"stop":2443.404,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But part -- but -- but the -- what meaning you give to defense and fundamentally what your attitude is toward this problem and that's the great division in the cases below.","start":2443.404,"stop":2455.444,"duration":12.04},{"text":"Articulated this jurisdiction where the fact of the matter is some of the law of 0court judges have specifically with McNabb, the plaintiff's (Inaudible) status.","start":2455.444,"stop":2463.875,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Isn't it in their own writing?","start":2463.875,"stop":2466.505,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, essentially our position, and I suppose I should touch on the other points here.","start":2466.505,"stop":2470.945,"duration":4.44},{"text":"Essentially our position here is that the consequences to law enforcement the -- are -- are the mechanical interpretation would be such that we don't think that the court should take that step.","start":2470.945,"stop":2484.906,"duration":13.96},{"text":"That if you have suggestion of coercion for the whole or psychological course, the confession goes on.","start":2484.906,"stop":2491.126,"duration":6.22},{"text":"That if you have the -- the McNabb kind of a -- I mean the Upshaw kind of situation where the police pulled a man in and questioned him for 30 hours as they say for the sole purpose of getting a confession.","start":2491.126,"stop":2503.737,"duration":12.61},{"text":"We can see that the McNabb rule applies.","start":2503.737,"stop":2506.977,"duration":3.24},{"text":"But though we say that there are other cases of which this is an illustration where this shouldn't be applied that --- that it should be said that it's reasonable for the police to engage in brief periods of investigation which resulted in this case in bringing two suspects and holding one.","start":2506.977,"stop":2526.331,"duration":19.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your were to say it's a question of the motive of the police.","start":2526.331,"stop":2530.481,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In part.","start":2530.481,"stop":2531.001,"duration":0.52},{"text":"It's a question of the motive --","start":2531.001,"stop":2532.841,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You know that in this case --","start":2532.841,"stop":2533.851,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and how they did it.","start":2533.851,"stop":2534.891,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's -- if I may say so your difficulty with the rule you were tending.","start":2534.891,"stop":2538.811,"duration":3.92},{"text":"Once you say reasonable as against mechanical.","start":2538.811,"stop":2542.171,"duration":3.36},{"text":"I don't think those are the (Inaudible) If it's reasonable, then what you said of them a while ago that this was done with -- they never thought they were doing anything illegal.","start":2542.171,"stop":2552.431,"duration":10.26},{"text":"They had self-consciousness of doing right.","start":2552.431,"stop":2555.138,"duration":2.71},{"text":"(Inaudible) is true but that leaves it open to the police authorities to hold on without presenting him, that without arraignment so long as they're satisfied, they're doing something conscientious if you please.","start":2555.138,"stop":2568.691,"duration":13.55}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, we don't --","start":2568.691,"stop":2569.221,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not merely -- not merely in fixing guilt on the suspect, but in establishing whether he is guilty lest they hold an innocent man.","start":2569.221,"stop":2576.791,"duration":7.57},{"text":"And that means that these conscientious police officials might have taken two days to establish that he was or wasn't the -- the potential -- I mean the criminal.","start":2576.791,"stop":2587.393,"duration":10.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Government's position isn't based solely on the conscientiousness of what the police did.","start":2587.393,"stop":2591.523,"duration":4.13},{"text":"I mean we take the position that the courts have to look not only at motive but what's actually right.","start":2591.523,"stop":2595.783,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But what was -- what was the criteria that it was a reasonable thing for police to do in order to ascertain whether this fellow was there or he wasn't there?","start":2595.783,"stop":2603.923,"duration":8.14},{"text":"That leaves out of the count a whole -- maybe for myself.","start":2603.923,"stop":2608.045,"duration":4.12},{"text":"The central concept of our prosecutorial system and the central concept that arraignment intervened in order to have the magistrate tell the fellow, \"You can keep your mouth shut.","start":2608.045,"stop":2620.165,"duration":12.12},{"text":"You don't have to say a thing.","start":2620.165,"stop":2621.345,"duration":1.18},{"text":"Do you want a lawyer?","start":2621.345,"stop":2622.655,"duration":1.31},{"text":"This is a capital offense.","start":2622.655,"stop":2623.773,"duration":1.12},{"text":"I'll give you a lawyer.\"","start":2623.773,"stop":2624.903,"duration":1.13},{"text":"All that is taken out and put into the discretionary, conscientious judgment of the police.","start":2624.903,"stop":2632.3,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the Government's position is that the -- the alternative should not be the mechanical rule that is suggested here that some --","start":2632.3,"stop":2642.733,"duration":10.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2642.733,"stop":2642.863,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- exercise of the rulemaking powers.","start":2642.863,"stop":2644.923,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) forthwith was stricken out.","start":2644.923,"stop":2648.713,"duration":3.79},{"text":"That forthwith is that you give it to kind of meeting as Justice Brennan said, that means that once you must (Inaudible) into it and there is stuck in there a judgment that's unnecessary mainly in relation to the function.","start":2648.713,"stop":2665.084,"duration":16.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask a question before you leave --","start":2665.084,"stop":2666.104,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2666.104,"stop":2666.504,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this -- earlier, Mr. Barrett, you suggested at page 42 though was an indication at least before the confession was signed, he'd been advised to something.","start":2666.504,"stop":2677.955,"duration":11.45},{"text":"Now, is there anything in that?","start":2677.955,"stop":2679.235,"duration":1.28},{"text":"I guess you're going to refer to us -- refers to what's at the bottom of 42 and the top of 43, were you not?","start":2679.235,"stop":2685.835,"duration":6.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2685.835,"stop":2686.235,"duration":0.4},{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":2686.235,"stop":2686.925,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2686.925,"stop":2686.945,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and then there was a paragraph -- this was not -- the written confession itself is not on this record.","start":2686.945,"stop":2692.105,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but what I wanted to ask you was this witness testified.","start":2692.105,"stop":2696.305,"duration":4.2},{"text":"I don't know who he was.","start":2696.305,"stop":2697.685,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He was an officer.","start":2697.685,"stop":2698.055,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But before he signed -- but before the statement was reduced to writing, he was advised of his rights.","start":2698.055,"stop":2704.065,"duration":6.01},{"text":"Now, at that time he wasn't advised of his right to be represented by counsel was he?","start":2704.065,"stop":2710.425,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All we know is what's here plus what the -- the opening paragraph of the -- of the confession have the usual statements about the -- the man was advised of his rights.","start":2710.425,"stop":2722.255,"duration":11.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, at the top though --","start":2722.255,"stop":2723.245,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2723.245,"stop":2723.355,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of page 43.","start":2723.355,"stop":2725.185,"duration":1.83},{"text":"This witness goes on to say, we told him that the statement would have to be voluntary.","start":2725.185,"stop":2729.885,"duration":4.7},{"text":"We put it down on his own words so the statement could be used for or against him in Court and he agreed to give the statement.","start":2729.885,"stop":2736.33,"duration":6.44},{"text":"Now, that's all that appears as to the rights of which he was advised.","start":2736.33,"stop":2740.266,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2740.266,"stop":2741.646,"duration":1.38},{"text":"Frankly I don't remember whether the -- the written confession went beyond and specifically mentioned counsel or not.","start":2741.646,"stop":2748.605,"duration":6.96},{"text":"It's not in this --","start":2748.605,"stop":2749.985,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a confession on the record?","start":2749.985,"stop":2751.605,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not on this.","start":2751.605,"stop":2752.025,"duration":0.42},{"text":"It's -- it's not in the printed transcript.","start":2752.025,"stop":2754.015,"duration":1.99},{"text":"No, sir.","start":2754.015,"stop":2754.925,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In -- in effect you are (Inaudible) are you not?","start":2754.925,"stop":2757.085,"duration":2.16},{"text":"That these three people, probable witnesses that you wanted to interrogate.","start":2757.085,"stop":2765.575,"duration":8.49},{"text":"And you claim that they had the right based on their asking -- they asked a question to the witness, that he wasn't on duty and have him arrested at that time or to take him before the Commissioner but he didn't have -- or enough evidence?","start":2765.575,"stop":2778.146,"duration":12.57}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":2778.146,"stop":2778.676,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If that's true, do you have it as statutory authority for summoning people as witness by the police or do you have to defend here on somehow rights to arrest him without a right to -- just because they -- they're a witness.","start":2778.676,"stop":2794.91,"duration":16.23}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The only thing that there -- is what -- that I'm aware of that there is, Your Honor, there is a -- a provision with respect to that under Rule 46 (b) of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure there's a provision which says that if the police think that a witness is about to flee the jurisdiction, they may, upon a proper showing to secure order placing him under bail or if he fails to give bail detaining him.","start":2794.91,"stop":2823.832,"duration":28.92},{"text":"But again that doesn't deal with the question of -- of their right to question.","start":2823.832,"stop":2828.162,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Even assuming that you had a right to interrogate them as witnesses is what I mean.","start":2828.162,"stop":2834.312,"duration":6.15},{"text":"If or under some kind of procedure, had you gone through any kind of procedure that was either legally authoring to do that or on its face permitted you to do it?","start":2834.312,"stop":2843.672,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm aware of -- of no statute that deals with the question beyond -- really beyond the Bill of Rights and that -- that specifically set out a procedure and for interrogating witnesses under these --- these circumstances.","start":2843.672,"stop":2862.847,"duration":19.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Barrett, if you were dealing with some crime that's obviously or apparently obviously a neighborhood crime, would you be justified in -- in taking all the young men who, in the neighborhood who might have been -- been suspected of this crime taking them to the jail and -- and holding them there under arrest until you had an opportunity to -- to examine them and determine whether they are guilty or -- or not?","start":2862.847,"stop":2892.813,"duration":29.97}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Normally I would assume that would be unreasonable.","start":2892.813,"stop":2895.293,"duration":2.48},{"text":"That --","start":2895.293,"stop":2895.743,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what is the difference?","start":2895.743,"stop":2898.223,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2898.223,"stop":2898.323,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2898.323,"stop":2898.953,"duration":0.63},{"text":"between that case and this.","start":2898.953,"stop":2900.493,"duration":1.54},{"text":"You -- you knew one -- only one person committed this crime.","start":2900.493,"stop":2904.303,"duration":3.81},{"text":"You arrest three persons on some theory or other and take them to -- you take them to the police station and you hold them there until you're satisfied that two of them didn't do it and one of them did.","start":2904.303,"stop":2918.512,"duration":14.21},{"text":"Now what is the difference between that and the one I put?","start":2918.512,"stop":2921.832,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Here, you have three young men who presumably could easily disappear.","start":2921.832,"stop":2927.822,"duration":5.99},{"text":"In fact two of them did disappear overnight.","start":2927.822,"stop":2932.282,"duration":4.46},{"text":"And the police had to go out and look for them.","start":2932.282,"stop":2934.402,"duration":2.12},{"text":"They didn't stay home, to find them, to question them.","start":2934.402,"stop":2939.568,"duration":5.17},{"text":"They had to engage evidently in detective work to find these people to -- to bring them in for the purpose of questioning.","start":2939.568,"stop":2947.765,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barrett, was there not evidence that three or these three persons, the two nephews and the petitioner were seen to leave the apartment premises on the afternoon in question?","start":2947.765,"stop":2964.32,"duration":16.56}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There was -- there was some testimony in the -- in the record by -- it's not in this printed record here, with respect to somebody saw a colored man with certain clothes and description leaving the apartment house.","start":2964.32,"stop":2980.198,"duration":15.88}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":2980.198,"stop":2980.628,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The petitioner himself testified that he left.","start":2980.628,"stop":2983.108,"duration":2.48},{"text":"That his -- that his brother said, \"You better -- better go.","start":2983.108,"stop":2988.75,"duration":5.64},{"text":"The police are looking into this crime.\"","start":2988.75,"stop":2992.16,"duration":3.41},{"text":"One of his nephews testified that the brother had suggested that he and the petitioner make themselves scared because the police were -- were around investigating this crime which had taken place just outside their apartment.","start":2992.16,"stop":3009.055,"duration":16.89},{"text":"On the question of the search, say just a moment, it seems to the Government the problem here is quite different from the problem where you have a man held in custody.","start":3009.055,"stop":3021.199,"duration":12.14},{"text":"He denies that he committed the crime.","start":3021.199,"stop":3024.219,"duration":3.02},{"text":"He has said -- asked, \"Will you consent to search your premises?\"","start":3024.219,"stop":3027.86,"duration":3.64},{"text":"And he says yes.","start":3027.86,"stop":3028.95,"duration":1.09},{"text":"This essentially was the judge in the Higgins case from which the petitioner rely.","start":3028.95,"stop":3034.42,"duration":5.47},{"text":"Here it was more like the Mitchell case.","start":3034.42,"stop":3036.92,"duration":2.5},{"text":"This Court decided where it was only after the defendant had confessed to the crime so that he had made his confession to the crime that he then having confessed the crime said, \"Now, I let you search.\"","start":3036.92,"stop":3051.807,"duration":14.89},{"text":"And he signed a written consent So, it was explicit.","start":3051.807,"stop":3054.307,"duration":2.5},{"text":"There wasn't any problem to that to search.","start":3054.307,"stop":3057.744,"duration":3.44},{"text":"So, we -- we say that the -- the search stands or falls really on the confession.","start":3057.744,"stop":3062.924,"duration":5.18},{"text":"That -- that had once having voluntarily made a confession of the crime, this was essentially what happened in the Mitchell case, he confessed and then he said, \"You can go and -- and get this evidence.\"","start":3062.924,"stop":3076.14,"duration":13.22},{"text":"Now, on the question of the jury, position of the Government here that the judge did probably the only thing he could have done -- once the jury had asked a question.","start":3076.14,"stop":3093.16,"duration":17.02},{"text":"Now, we say you can't say, petitioner said that the jury was not concerned with this issue.","start":3093.16,"stop":3099,"duration":5.84},{"text":"Congress in its wisdom had seen fit to -- to create the situation where the penalty for the crime is either an indeterminate sentence for 10 to 30 years or death.","start":3099,"stop":3110.624,"duration":11.62},{"text":"The jury decides whether or not it shall be death.","start":3110.624,"stop":3114.274,"duration":3.65},{"text":"The judge then decides if they don't say death, what -- what it shall be up to a maximum of 10 to 30.","start":3114.274,"stop":3121.962,"duration":7.69},{"text":"Well, of course, the jury is sentencing here.","start":3121.962,"stop":3124.722,"duration":2.76},{"text":"The jury is deciding, \"Shall this man die?\"","start":3124.722,"stop":3129.253,"duration":4.53},{"text":"But it seems to us that the jury could not rationally decide that issue without knowing the alternatives.","start":3129.253,"stop":3136.933,"duration":7.68},{"text":"And once the jury asked the question that they did here, it's clear that they were speculating on the alternatives.","start":3136.933,"stop":3142.853,"duration":5.92},{"text":"What's going to happen to this man if we don't give him the death penalty?","start":3142.853,"stop":3147.413,"duration":4.56},{"text":"And can be it said that it's more of a prejudice to defendant to have speculation without fact or -- or to give them the fact.","start":3147.413,"stop":3160.518,"duration":13.11},{"text":"Now, as we find out in the footnote in our brief on page 39, Crow against United States which this Court, it was up on certiorari on another point.","start":3160.518,"stop":3169.444,"duration":8.93},{"text":"This Court provided certiorari.","start":3169.444,"stop":3171.384,"duration":1.94},{"text":"You have the situation come up and -- and the judge points us the other way.","start":3171.384,"stop":3175.104,"duration":3.72},{"text":"He refused to ask -- answer the jury's questions about probation.","start":3175.104,"stop":3177.544,"duration":2.44},{"text":"The jury wouldn't have him against the for death penalty anyway.","start":3177.544,"stop":3182.484,"duration":4.94},{"text":"Now, this is not the kind of a case where we can see that you do work the kind of a case where the instruction is apt to (Inaudible) the issue of reasonable doubt.","start":3182.484,"stop":3193.634,"duration":11.15},{"text":"That is where the jury is interested in -- is in seeing well if we find him guilty, he maybe able to get off in five years.","start":3193.634,"stop":3202.282,"duration":8.65},{"text":"And well we're not really sure whether he did but it's only five years, so we'll find him guilty.","start":3202.282,"stop":3206.886,"duration":4.6},{"text":"This -- this one is that kind of a case.","start":3206.886,"stop":3209.586,"duration":2.7},{"text":"The petitioner under the circumstances of this case what the jury said was clear.","start":3209.586,"stop":3214.476,"duration":4.89},{"text":"They have no question about guilt.","start":3214.476,"stop":3216.944,"duration":2.47},{"text":"This wasn't a question about being reasonable doubt as to guilt.","start":3216.944,"stop":3219.604,"duration":2.66},{"text":"Their ultimate finding I suppose was that.","start":3219.604,"stop":3222.534,"duration":2.93},{"text":"That what they were concerned with is, \"Do we give him the death penalty?\"","start":3222.534,"stop":3226.754,"duration":4.22},{"text":"And on the Winston case, the Court said they could consider the broad spectrum and -- and the Government's position is that -- that most certainly that they've asked the question.","start":3226.754,"stop":3237.964,"duration":11.21},{"text":"That they have raised the issue that they have come into the Court and said, \"Will he be held for his natural life only?\"","start":3237.964,"stop":3246.753,"duration":8.79},{"text":"The judge did here, the only reasonable thing to do.We suggested that if he's -- if he had refused to do this and the death penalty had been convicted, the counsel for the petitioner could with as much reason perhaps have argued that that was prejudicial to the defendant under the circumstances.","start":3246.753,"stop":3266.428,"duration":19.67},{"text":"Arguing then that well, maybe they thought he would only get two years or five years.","start":3266.428,"stop":3270.838,"duration":4.41},{"text":"So, you wouldn't know what they thought his -- his ultimate period of incarceration would be.","start":3270.838,"stop":3277.238,"duration":6.4},{"text":"So, our contention essentially then is that -- that once they made the issue was certainly irrelevant that the issue they would decide, should the man die?","start":3277.238,"stop":3286.725,"duration":9.49},{"text":"And this can't be decided solely in terms of the -- of the crime and the nature and the circumstances as the jury is bound to want to know if there's evidence here, what's the alternative?","start":3286.725,"stop":3297.525,"duration":10.8},{"text":"Now, it may be that the unfortunate thing here is that Congress fixed these alternatives so far apart and that -- and that the -- perhaps that is the -- maybe if the alternatives had been life and death, the Court would have found that the jury would not have found death.","start":3297.525,"stop":3315.847,"duration":18.32},{"text":"But that's that fault of -- of the statute, not with what the judge did here.","start":3315.847,"stop":3320.28,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barrett, tell me, is that unfair?","start":3320.28,"stop":3321.67,"duration":1.39},{"text":"Is it unreasonable that -- improper for the -- intellectually improper for me to say that the innuendo of the jury's question was perfectly plain?","start":3321.67,"stop":3336.316,"duration":14.65},{"text":"Can we the jury be assured that the defendant legally be imprisoned for the remainder of his natural life?","start":3336.316,"stop":3343.722,"duration":7.41},{"text":"Is it -- is it -- am I entitled with intellectual honesty to say what was behind that question is perfectly plain?","start":3343.722,"stop":3353.496,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose so, but I don't think --","start":3353.496,"stop":3354.896,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":3354.896,"stop":3355.036,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that is prejudicial.","start":3355.036,"stop":3355.816,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not -- I didn't -- I didn't mean -- (Inaudible)","start":3355.816,"stop":3356.856,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":3356.856,"stop":3357.276,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to ask you --","start":3357.276,"stop":3357.606,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3357.606,"stop":3359.196,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't mean to ask you -- I didn't mean to ask them question.","start":3359.196,"stop":3360.326,"duration":1.13},{"text":"What I'm asking you is -- is that because they have -- they have to wait?","start":3360.326,"stop":3364.916,"duration":4.59},{"text":"Is it fair to say that that jury wanted -- the question was supported by the jury in order to get reassurance that they can be -- that they can be assured that you -- am I entitled to.","start":3364.916,"stop":3378.732,"duration":13.82},{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3378.732,"stop":3379.032,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, we don't know.","start":3379.032,"stop":3380.122,"duration":1.09},{"text":"But on the face --","start":3380.122,"stop":3380.502,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3380.502,"stop":3380.682,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of it I think it was just certainly reasonable to -- to say that the jury must have been thinking at this time that under the circumstances of this crime, they didn't want this man released in the hopes and the fear that there might be another similar crime and that this was what was back of their question.","start":3380.682,"stop":3398.123,"duration":17.44},{"text":"Now I don't suppose -- we take the position this is not improper.","start":3398.123,"stop":3401.763,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why not?","start":3401.763,"stop":3402.103,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that the jury in a sense when you give the jury this power, this is one of the things they're bound to consider.","start":3402.103,"stop":3408.287,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that's -- that's really what --","start":3408.287,"stop":3409.247,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":3409.247,"stop":3410.247,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this case imposes the Court with, doesn't it?","start":3410.247,"stop":3414.687,"duration":4.44},{"text":"That --","start":3414.687,"stop":3414.727,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3414.727,"stop":3415.117,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that -- that's what I think ultimately the question we get to whether the jury is entitled in a case like this to have this Court's state with accuracy relevant items in having the jury makes up its mind.","start":3415.117,"stop":3429.975,"duration":14.86},{"text":"Isn't that -- isn't that a fair statement on what we're up against?","start":3429.975,"stop":3435.825,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, except there is some -- I suppose some distinction should be drawn at the point which the judge states them.","start":3435.825,"stop":3441.165,"duration":5.34},{"text":"I mean the question of whether he should do it with the original charge.","start":3441.165,"stop":3443.535,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not --","start":3443.535,"stop":3444.135,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes or -- or whether he's attempting to resolve the question.","start":3444.135,"stop":3444.935,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but I'm assuming this case, there's nothing about it and they asked that question which I think you're happy to be right in this question naturally may bounce into their into heads and then the question is, assuming you gave them accurate answer should we give them give an accurate answer if we've have and we got no problem.","start":3444.935,"stop":3465.022,"duration":20.09},{"text":"If he has this is your entitlement to get that aid from the Court under this kind of a statute.","start":3465.022,"stop":3471.852,"duration":6.83},{"text":"That's really what they're asking.","start":3471.852,"stop":3472.862,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And our -- and our position is that -- that given the inevitability of the jury considering this question that -- that the defendant is less prejudiced by them having accurate information than they -- than the defendant would be about your speculation.","start":3472.862,"stop":3488.961,"duration":16.1},{"text":"Certainly you cannot say that playing it other way would not be the right -- giving any the death penalty.","start":3488.961,"stop":3493.831,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- certainly the jury can tell me and then ask the judge for a lot of the instructions or statements of accurate statement on his part helping them to make their thinking more relevant, more rational and more disciplined.","start":3493.831,"stop":3512.041,"duration":18.21},{"text":"And certainly we wouldn't allow him to say, \"Well, I think looking at this, this is a fact.\"","start":3512.041,"stop":3517.06,"duration":5.02},{"text":"He couldn't do that could he?","start":3517.06,"stop":3518.51,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3518.51,"stop":3518.79,"duration":0.28},{"text":"But certainly obviously limits on how far this can go.","start":3518.79,"stop":3520.28,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3520.28,"stop":3520.91,"duration":0.63},{"text":"I mean even as the things that would help him.","start":3520.91,"stop":3523.87,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose -- suppose the judges put that in his charge, would have been all right?","start":3523.87,"stop":3532.236,"duration":8.37}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, we don't face that here.","start":3532.236,"stop":3533.326,"duration":1.09},{"text":"Our -- the Government's feeling is that certainly that the defendant would have -- petitioner would have a better argument there because the judge would be raising the issue, putting it in effect in the jury's mind.","start":3533.326,"stop":3545.983,"duration":12.66},{"text":"Here, we -- we know it was in the jury's mind.","start":3545.983,"stop":3549.244,"duration":3.26},{"text":"And the judge didn't put it there.","start":3549.244,"stop":3551.034,"duration":1.79},{"text":"And the only question here is what really was it seriously prejudicial to the defendant, once it was in the jury's mind and the jury had asked the question to them go to the -- to give them the information.","start":3551.034,"stop":3562.494,"duration":11.46}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, has the judge the right to say anything to them after they have been charged and they've gone into the jury room that he wouldn't have been authorized to -- to tell them in the charge?","start":3562.494,"stop":3574.646,"duration":12.15}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I assume that the -- that the only question here is the general question of whether what happened here was unduly prejudicial to -- to the defendant.","start":3574.646,"stop":3584.373,"duration":9.73},{"text":"And I -- I don't suppose we can answer that in terms of the rights of the judge.","start":3584.373,"stop":3588.162,"duration":3.79},{"text":"We have to answer it in the terms of -- of in what the judge do -- that it's the judge's action here given the circumstances a -- a prejudicial action.","start":3588.162,"stop":3599.792,"duration":11.63}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, tell me, Mr. Barrett, on page 105, with the close of his charge, on this question, the judge says in that event, the defendant will be subject to imprisonment which the Court will impose but will not be subject to the death penalty.","start":3599.792,"stop":3615.36,"duration":15.57},{"text":"Suppose he said in that event the defendant will be subject to imprisonment up to 30 years which the Court will impose but will not be subject to the death penalty.","start":3615.36,"stop":3624.945,"duration":9.59},{"text":"Do you think that would have been error in the charge?","start":3624.945,"stop":3631.195,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Our position would be, no.","start":3631.195,"stop":3632.982,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That it would not be?","start":3632.982,"stop":3633.342,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If that's as far as he went.","start":3633.342,"stop":3635.092,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose he went farther and said that the Parole Board may -- may release him much sooner even -- even on one third.","start":3635.092,"stop":3643.336,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, for that --","start":3643.336,"stop":3643.376,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And he could stand of one third of the sentence of 30 years?","start":3643.376,"stop":3646.786,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That I think the Government's position that -- I -- I can't say what position the Government would take on that point.","start":3646.786,"stop":3651.396,"duration":4.61},{"text":"But certainly the defendant would have a better argument than he has here of prejudice, simply because here, it was the -- he would then be putting the parole system into the minds of the jury for their consideration affirmatively.","start":3651.396,"stop":3665.5,"duration":14.1},{"text":"Here, the jury raised the issue.","start":3665.5,"stop":3667.71,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not the Parole Board.","start":3667.71,"stop":3669.53,"duration":1.82},{"text":"They just want to get generally how much -- how soon is this fellow likely to get outside?","start":3669.53,"stop":3673.639,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is the right to (Inaudible)","start":3673.639,"stop":3674.689,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3674.689,"stop":3675.599,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, on another question that was asked when Mr. Bryant was here.","start":3675.599,"stop":3680.659,"duration":5.06},{"text":"We assume that -- that if this case is -- would -- were reversed on the issue of the charge here, it would have to be retried.","start":3680.659,"stop":3688.859,"duration":8.2},{"text":"But the statute confers upon the jury the discretion of deciding whether or not that shall be given.","start":3688.859,"stop":3696.022,"duration":7.16},{"text":"And it certainly cannot be said here as a matter of law the jury was wrong in giving the death penalty.","start":3696.022,"stop":3703.302,"duration":7.28},{"text":"And that if the case goes back, presumably, it will have to be retried before another jury and give them an opportunity to exercise the -- the discretion that's involved here because there seems to be -- it seems -- it seems to be a difficult case and needs to separate these two things out since under the statute, the jury has the discretion to decide.","start":3703.302,"stop":3726.77,"duration":23.47},{"text":"And it's not the kind of a case in which an appellate court can say as a matter of law they should have decided it the other way.","start":3726.77,"stop":3733.6,"duration":6.83},{"text":"It's just like any other case where there was an error committed and it -- it's found to be prejudicial, it would then go back.","start":3733.6,"stop":3742.647,"duration":9.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there -- may I ask if that -- are there any authorities on this last question?","start":3742.647,"stop":3747.573,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There are no --","start":3747.573,"stop":3747.983,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3747.983,"stop":3748.833,"duration":0.85},{"text":"it's your logical analysis?","start":3748.833,"stop":3751.413,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right on this last point.","start":3751.413,"stop":3752.543,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there's no -- there are no --?","start":3752.543,"stop":3754.174,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Edward L. Barrett, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not that I'm aware of.","start":3754.174,"stop":3757.574,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant.","start":3757.574,"stop":3759.394,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":3759.394,"stop":3760.574,"duration":1.18},{"text":"About two to three minutes of my --","start":3760.574,"stop":3762.485,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Take your time.","start":3762.485,"stop":3762.795,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"-- remaining time.","start":3762.795,"stop":3763.665,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You have more time.","start":3763.665,"stop":3765.225,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"As to the business of the instruction, the supplemental instruction, I would like to -- just to have one word to say on this.","start":3765.225,"stop":3773.739,"duration":8.51},{"text":"I think that the cases which are on the books up to now and the cases on which the Government draws its rationale relative to the propriety of the judge making comment about the business of parole or how soon he's going to get out.","start":3773.739,"stop":3790.251,"duration":16.51},{"text":"Have -- those cases have to do with those instances where the jury is charged with the duty of fixing punishment as a matter of fact.","start":3790.251,"stop":3798.699,"duration":8.45},{"text":"In this particular case, it seems that the jury was seeking -- wasn't seeking information about a matter which was properly within their (Inaudible) of consideration.","start":3798.699,"stop":3811.821,"duration":13.12},{"text":"They were not to consider any alternative sentences.","start":3811.821,"stop":3815.441,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Actually what the jury did by way of -- I -- I like the term innuendo.","start":3815.441,"stop":3819.722,"duration":4.28},{"text":"By innuendo, the jury was trying to get a commitment from the judge as to what you're going to do with him if we don't kill him.","start":3819.722,"stop":3827.368,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, tell me, Mr. Bryant, if that interpolation which I suggest to Mr. Barrett, had appeared in the charge, in other words up to 30 years if they'd have","start":3827.368,"stop":3836.323,"duration":8.95},{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3836.323,"stop":3836.453,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Did wrong, Your Honor.","start":3836.453,"stop":3837.383,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Up to 30 years.","start":3837.383,"stop":3838.623,"duration":1.24},{"text":"Now, my question is, do you suppose the question which finally was asked whatever has been asked?","start":3838.623,"stop":3846.274,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they might very well to come in and ask the judge then if you give him 30 years, is that -- does that mean he's right?","start":3846.274,"stop":3852.238,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, at least I asked it that way.","start":3852.238,"stop":3853.758,"duration":1.52},{"text":"Don't you suppose that's -- there's at least one possible inference from the form of the jury's question that the jury has-- and a fact that's cited that if this man would be kept imprisoned for the rest of his life, they wouldn't give him the chair.","start":3853.758,"stop":3868.432,"duration":14.67},{"text":"But if he was not to be imprisoned for the rest of his life, then they would bring in the death penalty.","start":3868.432,"stop":3873.858,"duration":5.43},{"text":"At least isn't that final?","start":3873.858,"stop":3874.528,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"I was looking for that.","start":3874.528,"stop":3875.338,"duration":0.81},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3875.338,"stop":3875.958,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless on that interpretation of it that the judge had said, \"I can sentence him up to 30 years.\"","start":3875.958,"stop":3881.457,"duration":5.5},{"text":"There would not have been any necessity to ask a question, would there, because in that event they don't have the information they wanted without asking the question.","start":3881.457,"stop":3888.037,"duration":6.58}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3888.037,"stop":3889.277,"duration":1.24},{"text":"And it would have been highly -- highly improper for them to give him that inference.","start":3889.277,"stop":3892.841,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, why?","start":3892.841,"stop":3893.441,"duration":0.6},{"text":"That's the next question that's been asked.","start":3893.441,"stop":3894.761,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, for this reason if Your Honor pleases.","start":3894.761,"stop":3897.021,"duration":2.26},{"text":"I think that determining whether or not the comment is proper or not, we have to analyze the due response.","start":3897.021,"stop":3902.201,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm getting back now.","start":3902.201,"stop":3903.111,"duration":0.91},{"text":"The -- the -- suppose all that have been done here was that the charge had added up to 30 years.","start":3903.111,"stop":3908.522,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3908.522,"stop":3908.682,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that have been wrong?","start":3908.682,"stop":3909.932,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it is not the -- the province of the jury to know about what the alternative punishment.","start":3909.932,"stop":3914.802,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":3914.802,"stop":3915.862,"duration":1.06},{"text":"Will be subject to imprisonment up to 30 years.","start":3915.862,"stop":3918.016,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Up to 30 years, would there also have been prejudicial errors?","start":3918.016,"stop":3920.806,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, if Your Honor please.","start":3920.806,"stop":3921.946,"duration":1.14},{"text":"And I say this as to whether or not it's given to him gratuitously or in answer to question.","start":3921.946,"stop":3926.767,"duration":4.82},{"text":"I think that --","start":3926.767,"stop":3926.987,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in this case.","start":3926.987,"stop":3928.067,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":3928.067,"stop":3928.587,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Our case is a little different.","start":3928.587,"stop":3930.417,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Our case --","start":3930.417,"stop":3931.577,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3931.577,"stop":3931.717,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"This case is a little different.","start":3931.717,"stop":3932.887,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":3932.887,"stop":3933.777,"duration":0.89},{"text":"Our case is a little different.","start":3933.777,"stop":3935.936,"duration":2.16},{"text":"Now, just on the McNabb, I want to say one final word on the McNabb point.","start":3935.936,"stop":3941.706,"duration":5.77},{"text":"That it seems that the history of the committing -- committing the legislation indicates the language without unnecessary delay would certainly be interpreted to -- to permit delay or procrastination only because of the unavailability of committing authorities.","start":3941.706,"stop":3960.234,"duration":18.53},{"text":"And I say that for this reason.","start":3960.234,"stop":3961.484,"duration":1.25},{"text":"In the District of Columbia Circuit, over a period of time, they have -- there's been some interpretation of this rule and one of the judges or -- or two of them has seen fit to concur especially in some of those cases for this reason.","start":3961.484,"stop":3979.889,"duration":18.41},{"text":"They have determined that the delay was not -- was not unnecessary by virtue of late evening arrest or Sunday arrest or holiday arrest.","start":3979.889,"stop":3989.6,"duration":9.71},{"text":"In other words, the question of necessary is still determined by the availability of the Commissioner and the element of choice.","start":3989.6,"stop":3997.88,"duration":8.28},{"text":"If the authorities choose to delay for the purpose of the interrogation, then that delay certainly, is at that time illegal.","start":3997.88,"stop":4008.875,"duration":10.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And Mr. Bryant, before you take your seat.","start":4008.875,"stop":4010.215,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":4010.215,"stop":4013.195,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court notices from the record in the case that you came into the case by appointment of the District Court?","start":4013.195,"stop":4020.405,"duration":7.21}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4020.405,"stop":4021.675,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And that you have carried this case through for an impecunious defendant through the Supreme Court of the United States and we would have you know that we consider this a distinct service to the cause of justice regardless of what the outcome of this case might be.","start":4021.675,"stop":4039.766,"duration":18.09}]},{"speakerName":"William B. Bryant","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":4039.766,"stop":4040.306,"duration":0.54},{"text":"It's my honor.","start":4040.306,"stop":4040.396,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Bryant, the Court said it doesn't detract one wit from the service you rendered the cause of justice through your representation of the Government in this very serious case.","start":4040.396,"stop":4051.605,"duration":11.21}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr 1, 1957","petitioner":"Mallory","respondent":"United States","docket":"521","citation":"354 US 449 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/354/449","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 24, 1957"}